1
00:00:00,320 --> 00:00:05,120
For online content creators the unavoidable 
subject of 2021 has been NFT’s. 

2
00:00:05,120 --> 00:00:10,080
From incredibly cringe-worthy ape profile pics, to 
incomprehensibly tasteless tributes to deceased  

3
00:00:10,080 --> 00:00:15,920
celebrities, to six-figure sales of the “original 
copy” of a meme, it is the thing that is currently  

4
00:00:15,920 --> 00:00:20,720
dominating the collective brain space of digital 
artists and sucking up all the oxygen in the room.

5
00:00:20,720 --> 00:00:25,520
And I do want to talk about that, I want to 
talk about my opinions on NFTs and digital  

6
00:00:25,520 --> 00:00:29,840
ownership and scarcity, all the myriad 
dimensions of the issue, but I don’t  

7
00:00:30,640 --> 00:00:37,440
just want to talk about NFTs, I can’t just talk 
about NFTs because ultimately they are just  

8
00:00:37,440 --> 00:00:42,720
a symbol of so much more, and it is that 
“more” that is ultimately important.

9
00:00:42,720 --> 00:00:57,840
So let me tell you a story.

10
00:01:11,080 --> 00:01:12,080
[Drumming]

11
00:01:12,080 --> 00:01:14,960
In 2008 the economy functionally collapsed.

12
00:01:14,960 --> 00:01:17,520
The basic chain reaction was this:

13
00:01:17,520 --> 00:01:20,400
Banks came up with a thing called 
a mortgage-backed security,  

14
00:01:20,400 --> 00:01:24,560
a financial instrument that could be traded 
or collected that was based on a bundle  

15
00:01:24,560 --> 00:01:29,680
of thousands of individual mortgages. Based on the 
general reluctance of banks to issue mortgages,  

16
00:01:29,680 --> 00:01:34,640
the risk-aversion in lending someone hundreds 
of thousands of dollars that they’ll pay off  

17
00:01:34,640 --> 00:01:40,720
over the course of decades, these bonds 
were seen as especially stable. However  

18
00:01:40,720 --> 00:01:47,440
they were also immensely profitable for the 
banks who both issue the mortgages and the bonds.

19
00:01:47,440 --> 00:01:51,120
Because of that perceived stability a 
lot of other financial organizations,  

20
00:01:51,120 --> 00:01:56,240
like pension funds and hedge funds, used them 
as the backbone of their investment portfolio.

21
00:01:56,240 --> 00:02:00,960
In this arrangement a mortgage becomes more 
profitable to the bank issuing the mortgage  

22
00:02:00,960 --> 00:02:06,800
as a component of a bond than it is as a 
mortgage. Proportionally the returns per  

23
00:02:06,800 --> 00:02:11,600
mortgage from the bond are just that much better 
than the returns from the isolated mortgage.

24
00:02:11,600 --> 00:02:16,240
There’s some problems, though. Problem one is 
that the biggest returns on a bond come from  

25
00:02:16,240 --> 00:02:21,040
when it first hits the market, a new bond 
that creates new securities sales is worth  

26
00:02:21,040 --> 00:02:27,280
more than an old bond that is slowly appreciating, 
but not seeing much trade. Problem two  

27
00:02:27,280 --> 00:02:30,880
is that there are a finite number 
of people and houses in America;  

28
00:02:30,880 --> 00:02:35,680
the market has to level out at a natural 
ceiling as eventually all or nearly all  

29
00:02:35,680 --> 00:02:40,880
mortgages are packaged into bonds, thus very 
few new bonds can be generated and sold.

30
00:02:40,880 --> 00:02:43,040
So here’s the incentives that are created.

31
00:02:43,040 --> 00:02:47,440
One: it’s good for banks if there are more 
houses that they can issue mortgages for 

32
00:02:48,080 --> 00:02:52,320
Two: the more mortgages issued the 
better, because a bad mortgage is  

33
00:02:52,320 --> 00:02:57,920
worth more as a component of a bond than 
a good mortgage that’s not part of a bond.

34
00:02:57,920 --> 00:03:02,960
So real estate developers find that they have a 
really easy time getting funding from banks for  

35
00:03:02,960 --> 00:03:06,880
creating vast new suburbs full of houses 
that can be sold to generate mortgages,  

36
00:03:06,880 --> 00:03:11,120
but rather than building the kind of 
housing most people actually need and want,  

37
00:03:11,120 --> 00:03:16,400
they focus specifically on the kinds of 
upper-middle-class houses that fit into the sweet  

38
00:03:16,400 --> 00:03:21,680
spot from the perspective of the banks packaging 
the bonds. Buyers, in turn, find that they have a  

39
00:03:21,680 --> 00:03:27,600
suspiciously easy time getting a mortgage despite 
the fact that, for most people, the economy wasn’t  

40
00:03:27,600 --> 00:03:33,200
doing so great. Wages were stagnant and yet even 
though developers were going absolutely haywire  

41
00:03:33,200 --> 00:03:37,520
building new housing, the houses being built 
were all out of their price range to begin with,  

42
00:03:37,520 --> 00:03:44,640
and counter intuitively this massive increase 
in supply wasn’t driving down the price.

43
00:03:44,640 --> 00:03:49,760
This is because the houses were being bought, just 
mostly not by people intending to live in them.  

44
00:03:49,760 --> 00:03:54,400
They were being bought by speculators who 
would then maybe rent them out or often just  

45
00:03:54,400 --> 00:03:57,920
leave them vacant with the intent 
to sell a couple years later.

46
00:03:57,920 --> 00:04:02,800
Because speculators were buying up the supply 
it created synthetic demand. The price keeps  

47
00:04:02,800 --> 00:04:08,480
going up because speculators keep buying, which 
creates the illusion that the value is going up,  

48
00:04:08,480 --> 00:04:13,600
which attracts more speculators who buy up 
more supply and further inflate the price.

49
00:04:13,600 --> 00:04:18,160
These speculators are enabled by a system 
that is prioritizing generating new mortgages  

50
00:04:18,160 --> 00:04:22,160
purely for the sake of having more 
mortgages to package into bonds.  

51
00:04:22,160 --> 00:04:26,400
The down payments are low and the mortgages 
all have a really attractive teaser rate,  

52
00:04:26,400 --> 00:04:31,280
meaning that for the first three to seven years of 
the mortgage the monthly payments are rock bottom,  

53
00:04:31,280 --> 00:04:36,480
as low as a few hundred dollars per month against 
a mortgage that would normally charge thousands.

54
00:04:36,480 --> 00:04:40,560
Caught up in all this are legitimate 
buyers who have been lured into signing  

55
00:04:40,560 --> 00:04:44,640
for a mortgage that they can’t afford 
by aggressive salespeople who have an  

56
00:04:44,640 --> 00:04:49,040
incentive to generate mortgages that they can 
then sell to a bank who can put it into a bond  

57
00:04:49,040 --> 00:04:53,840
to sell to pension funds to make a line go 
up, because it’s good when the line goes up.

58
00:04:53,840 --> 00:04:54,880
It’s a bubble.

59
00:04:54,880 --> 00:04:58,560
The bubble burst as the teaser rates 
on the mortgages started to expire,  

60
00:04:58,560 --> 00:05:02,000
the monthly cost jumped up, and 
since the demand was synthetic  

61
00:05:02,000 --> 00:05:06,160
there were no actual buyers for the 
speculators to sell the houses to.

62
00:05:06,160 --> 00:05:11,040
So the speculators start dumping stock, which 
finally drives prices down, but because the  

63
00:05:11,040 --> 00:05:16,880
original price was so inflated the new price 
is still out of reach of most actual buyers.

64
00:05:16,880 --> 00:05:20,400
Legitimate buyers caught in the 
middle find their rates jumping, too,  

65
00:05:20,400 --> 00:05:24,880
but because the price of the house is going 
down as speculators try and dump their stock  

66
00:05:24,880 --> 00:05:28,800
the price of the house goes down 
relative to the mortgage issued,  

67
00:05:28,800 --> 00:05:33,120
and thus they can’t refinance and are 
locked into paying the original terms.

68
00:05:33,120 --> 00:05:36,400
Unable to sell the house and unable 
to afford the monthly payments,  

69
00:05:36,400 --> 00:05:41,840
the owners, legitimate and speculators, 
default on their mortgages, they stop paying.

70
00:05:41,840 --> 00:05:46,480
Eventually the default rate reaches 
criticality and the bonds fail.  

71
00:05:46,480 --> 00:05:52,640
As the bonds fail this impacts all the first order 
buyers of the bonds, hedge funds, pension funds,  

72
00:05:52,640 --> 00:05:57,920
retirement savings funds, and the like. 
It also cascades through all derivatives,  

73
00:05:57,920 --> 00:06:03,120
which are financial products that take their 
value directly from the value of the bond.

74
00:06:03,120 --> 00:06:08,400
This creates a knock-on effect: huge segments 
of the economy turn out to be dead trees,  

75
00:06:08,400 --> 00:06:12,560
rotten to the core, but as a rotten tree falls  

76
00:06:12,560 --> 00:06:16,400
it still shreds its neighbours 
and crushes anything below it.

77
00:06:16,400 --> 00:06:20,320
It was a failure precipitated by a 
combination of greed, active fraud,  

78
00:06:20,320 --> 00:06:25,360
and willful blindness at all levels of power. 
The banks issuing the bad mortgages were the same  

79
00:06:25,360 --> 00:06:30,000
banks selling the bonds and providing the capital 
to build the houses to generate the mortgages.  

80
00:06:30,000 --> 00:06:34,480
The ratings agencies checking the bonds were, 
themselves, publicly traded and dependent  

81
00:06:34,480 --> 00:06:39,120
on being in good relations with the banks, 
incentivized to rubber stamp whatever rating  

82
00:06:39,120 --> 00:06:44,240
would make their client happy. The regulatory 
agencies that should have seen the problem coming  

83
00:06:44,240 --> 00:06:47,920
were gutted by budget cuts and mired 
in conflicts of interest as employees  

84
00:06:47,920 --> 00:06:52,080
used their positions in regulation to 
secure higher paying jobs in industry.  

85
00:06:52,080 --> 00:06:57,040
And, the cherry on top, the people largely 
responsible for it all knew that because they  

86
00:06:57,040 --> 00:07:02,000
and their toxic products were so interwoven into 
the foundations of the economy they could count  

87
00:07:02,000 --> 00:07:15,840
on a bailout from the government because no matter 
how rotten they were, they were very large trees.

88
00:07:17,880 --> 00:07:18,880
[Drumming]

89
00:07:18,880 --> 00:07:23,280
This naked display of greed and fraud 
created what would be fertile soil for  

90
00:07:23,280 --> 00:07:26,640
both anti-capitalist movements 
and hyper-capitalist movements:  

91
00:07:26,640 --> 00:07:31,280
both groups of people who saw themselves as 
being screwed over by the system, with one  

92
00:07:31,280 --> 00:07:37,040
group diagnosing the problem as the system’s 
inherently corrupt and corrupting incentives,  

93
00:07:37,040 --> 00:07:43,440
and the other seeing the crisis as a consequence 
of too much regulation, too much exclusion.

94
00:07:43,440 --> 00:07:48,080
The hyper-capitalist, or anarcho-capitalist 
argument is that in a less constrained  

95
00:07:48,080 --> 00:07:53,520
market there would be more incentive to call 
foul, that regulation had only succeeded in  

96
00:07:53,520 --> 00:07:58,320
creating an in-group that was effectively 
able to conspire without competition.

97
00:07:58,320 --> 00:08:01,440
Of course this argument fails to 
consider that a substantial number of  

98
00:08:01,440 --> 00:08:06,240
people within the system did, in fact, get 
fabulously wealthy specifically by betting  

99
00:08:06,240 --> 00:08:09,280
against the synthetic success 
of the market, but regardless.

100
00:08:09,840 --> 00:08:15,920
Into this environment in 2009 arrived Bitcoin, 
an all-electronic peer-to-peer currency.  

101
00:08:15,920 --> 00:08:19,280
Philosophically Bitcoin, and 
cryptocurrency in general,  

102
00:08:19,280 --> 00:08:23,520
was paraded as an end to banks 
and centralized currency.

103
00:08:23,520 --> 00:08:27,200
This is what will form the bedrock, 
both philosophical and technological,  

104
00:08:27,200 --> 00:08:30,560
that NFTs will be built on 
top of. It’s a bit of a hike  

105
00:08:30,560 --> 00:08:35,919
from here to the Bored Ape Yacht Club, 
so I guess get ready for that. Strap in.

106
00:08:35,919 --> 00:08:41,599
As we get into this we’re going to need to deal 
with a lot of vocabulary, and a lot of complexity.  

107
00:08:41,600 --> 00:08:44,880
Some of this is the result of systems 
that are very technically intricate,  

108
00:08:44,880 --> 00:08:48,320
and some of this is from systems that 
are poorly designed or deliberately  

109
00:08:48,320 --> 00:08:53,040
obtuse in order to make them difficult to 
understand and thus appear more legitimate.

110
00:08:53,040 --> 00:08:57,280
The entire subject sits at the intersection 
of two fields that are notoriously prone to  

111
00:08:57,280 --> 00:09:03,440
hype-based obfuscation, computer tech and finance, 
and inherits a lot of bad habits from both,  

112
00:09:03,440 --> 00:09:07,440
with a reputation for making things 
deliberately more difficult to understand  

113
00:09:07,440 --> 00:09:12,720
specifically to create the illusion that 
only they are smart enough to understand it.

114
00:09:12,720 --> 00:09:17,840
Mining and minting are both methods for making 
tokens, which are the base thing that blockchains  

115
00:09:17,840 --> 00:09:23,200
deal with, but the two are colloquially different 
processes, where mining is a coin token created as  

116
00:09:23,200 --> 00:09:28,160
a result of the consensus protocol and minting 
is a user-initiated addition of a token to a  

117
00:09:28,160 --> 00:09:32,800
blockchain. All blockchains are made of nodes, 
and these nodes can be watcher nodes, miner nodes,  

118
00:09:32,800 --> 00:09:37,760
or validator nodes, though most miner nodes are 
also validator nodes. Fractionalization is the  

119
00:09:37,760 --> 00:09:42,960
process of taking one asset and creating a new 
asset that represents portions of the original.

120
00:09:42,960 --> 00:09:48,960
So you get $DOG, a memecoin crypto DeFi venture 
capital fund backed by the fractionalization of  

121
00:09:48,960 --> 00:09:53,680
the original Doge meme sold as an NFT 
to PleasrDAO on the Ethereum network.

122
00:09:53,680 --> 00:09:57,920
I’m sorry, some of this is 
just going to be like that.

123
00:09:57,920 --> 00:10:02,240
The idea behind cryptocurrency is that 
your digital wallet functions the same as  

124
00:10:02,240 --> 00:10:06,800
a bank account, there’s no need for a bank 
to hold and process your transactions because  

125
00:10:06,800 --> 00:10:11,600
rather than holding a sum that conceptually 
represents physical currency, the cryptocoins  

126
00:10:11,600 --> 00:10:17,120
in your cryptowallet are the actual money. And 
because this money isn’t issued by a government  

127
00:10:17,120 --> 00:10:22,240
it is resistant to historical cash crises like 
hyperinflation caused by governments devaluing  

128
00:10:22,240 --> 00:10:27,760
their currency on purpose or by accident. It 
brings the flexibility and anonymity of cash and  

129
00:10:27,760 --> 00:10:33,520
barter to the digital realm, allowing individuals 
to transact without oversight or intermediaries.

130
00:10:33,520 --> 00:10:39,440
And in a one-paragraph pitch you can see the 
appeal, there’s a compelling narrative there.

131
00:10:39,440 --> 00:10:44,240
But, of course, in the twelve years since 
then none of that played out as designed.  

132
00:10:44,240 --> 00:10:48,240
Bitcoin was structurally too slow and 
expensive to handle regular commerce.  

133
00:10:48,240 --> 00:10:52,560
The whole thing basically came out the 
gate as a speculative financial vehicle  

134
00:10:52,560 --> 00:10:56,560
and so the only consumer market 
that proved to be a viable use  

135
00:10:56,560 --> 00:11:01,520
was buying and selling prohibited drugs where 
the high fees, rapid price fluctuations,  

136
00:11:01,520 --> 00:11:08,320
and multi-hour transaction times were mitigated 
by receiving LSD in the mail a week later.

137
00:11:08,320 --> 00:11:12,880
And as far as banking is concerned, Bitcoin 
was never designed to solve the actual problems  

138
00:11:12,880 --> 00:11:18,400
created by the banking industry, only to be the 
new medium by which they operated. The principal  

139
00:11:18,400 --> 00:11:23,280
offering wasn’t revolution, but at best a changing 
of the guard. The gripe is not with the outcomes  

140
00:11:23,280 --> 00:11:29,680
of 2008, but the fact that you had to be well 
connected in order to get in on the grift in 2006.

141
00:11:29,680 --> 00:11:34,480
And even the change of the guard is an illusion. 
Old money finance assholes like the Winkelvoss  

142
00:11:34,480 --> 00:11:39,360
twins were some of the first big names to jump 
