160
00:12:56,880 --> 00:13:03,360
This is a really important point to stress: 
cryptocurrency does nothing to address 99% of  

161
00:13:03,360 --> 00:13:08,800
the problems with the banking industry, because 
those problems are patterns of human behaviour.  

162
00:13:08,800 --> 00:13:13,680
They’re incentives, they’re social structures, 
they’re modalities. The problem is what people  

163
00:13:13,680 --> 00:13:20,320
are doing to others, not that the building they’re 
doing it in has the word “bank” on the outside.

164
00:13:20,320 --> 00:13:25,760
In addition to not fixing problems, Bitcoin 
also came with a pretty substantial drawback.

165
00:13:25,760 --> 00:13:30,320
The innovation of Bitcoin over previous attempts 
at digital currency was to employ a distributed  

166
00:13:30,320 --> 00:13:35,680
append-only ledger, a kind of database where new 
entries can only be added to the end, and then to  

167
00:13:35,680 --> 00:13:41,360
have several different nodes, called validators, 
compete over who gets to validate the next update.

168
00:13:41,360 --> 00:13:46,480
These are, respectively, the blockchain, 
and proof-of-work verification.

169
00:13:46,480 --> 00:13:50,480
Now, proof-of-work has an interesting 
history as a technology, typically being  

170
00:13:50,480 --> 00:13:55,920
deployed as a deterrent to misbehaviour. For 
example, if you require that for every email  

171
00:13:55,920 --> 00:14:01,520
sent the user’s computer has to complete a 
small math problem it places a trivial load  

172
00:14:01,520 --> 00:14:06,000
onto normal users sending a few dozen, 
or even a couple hundred emails a day,  

173
00:14:06,000 --> 00:14:11,600
but places a massive load on the infrastructure 
of anyone attempting to spam millions of emails.

174
00:14:12,160 --> 00:14:16,160
How it works in Bitcoin, simply put, is 
that when a block of transactions are  

175
00:14:16,160 --> 00:14:20,800
ready to be recorded to the ledger all of the 
mining nodes in the network compete with one  

176
00:14:20,800 --> 00:14:26,080
another to solve a cryptographic math problem 
that’s based on the data inside the block.

177
00:14:26,640 --> 00:14:31,760
Effectively they’re competing to figure out 
the equation that yields a specific result  

178
00:14:31,760 --> 00:14:36,400
when the contents of the block are fed into 
it, with the complexity of the desired result  

179
00:14:36,400 --> 00:14:41,600
getting deliberately more difficult based on the 
total processing power available to the network.

180
00:14:42,160 --> 00:14:46,080
Once the math problem has been solved the 
rest of the validation network can easily  

181
00:14:46,080 --> 00:14:50,800
double-check the work, since the contents of 
the block can be fed into the proposed solution  

182
00:14:50,800 --> 00:14:54,080
and it either spits out the valid answer or fails.

183
00:14:54,080 --> 00:14:58,000
If the equation works and the consensus 
of validators signs off on it the block  

184
00:14:58,000 --> 00:15:01,440
is added to the bottom of the ledger and 
the miner who solved the problem first  

185
00:15:01,440 --> 00:15:04,080
is rewarded with newly generated Bitcoin.

186
00:15:04,080 --> 00:15:08,560
The complexity of the answer that the computers 
are trying to solve scales up based on the  

187
00:15:08,560 --> 00:15:14,000
network’s processing power specifically to 
incur heavy diminishing returns as a protection  

188
00:15:14,000 --> 00:15:19,440
against an attack on the network where someone 
just builds a bigger computer and takes over.

189
00:15:19,440 --> 00:15:22,240
Critics pointed out that 
this created new problems:  

190
00:15:22,240 --> 00:15:27,600
adversarial validation would deliberately incur 
escalating processing costs, which would in turn  

191
00:15:27,600 --> 00:15:31,520
generate perverse structural incentives 
that would quickly reward capital holders  

192
00:15:31,520 --> 00:15:36,080
and lock out any individual that wasn’t already 
obscenely wealthy, because while the escalating  

193
00:15:36,080 --> 00:15:41,200
proof-of-work scheme incurs heavy diminishing 
returns, diminishing returns are still returns,  

194
00:15:41,200 --> 00:15:45,920
so more would always go to those with 
the resources to build the bigger rig.

195
00:15:45,920 --> 00:15:48,560
No matter what Bitcoin future was envisioned,  

196
00:15:48,560 --> 00:15:52,640
in the here and now computer 
hardware can be bought with dollars.

197
00:15:52,640 --> 00:15:55,040
Rather than dismantling corrupt power structures,  

198
00:15:55,040 --> 00:15:58,320
this would just become a new 
tool for existing wealth.

199
00:15:58,320 --> 00:16:01,840
And that’s… exactly what happened.

200
00:16:01,840 --> 00:16:06,880
Thus began an arms race for bigger and bigger 
processing rigs, followed by escalating demands  

201
00:16:06,880 --> 00:16:12,880
for the support systems, hardware engineers, HVAC, 
and operating space needed to put those rigs in.

202
00:16:12,880 --> 00:16:16,480
And, don’t worry, we’re not 
forgetting the power requirements.

203
00:16:16,480 --> 00:16:20,960
These rigs draw an industrial amount of 
power and, because of the winner-takes-all  

204
00:16:20,960 --> 00:16:26,080
nature of the competition, huge amounts of 
redundant work are being done and discarded.

205
00:16:26,080 --> 00:16:30,560
Estimates for this power consumption are 
hard to verify, the data is very complex,  

206
00:16:30,560 --> 00:16:34,000
spread across hundreds of operators 
around the globe, who move frequently  

207
00:16:34,000 --> 00:16:39,040
in search of cheap electricity, and 
it’s all pretty heavily politicized.

208
00:16:39,040 --> 00:16:44,240
But even conservative estimates from within the 
crypto-mining industry puts the sum energy cost  

209
00:16:44,240 --> 00:16:49,680
of Bitcoin processing on par with the power 
consumption of a small industrialized nation.

210
00:16:49,680 --> 00:16:54,880
Now, evangelists will counter that the global 
banking industry also uses a lot of power,  

211
00:16:54,880 --> 00:17:00,880
gesturing at things like idle ATMs humming away 
all night long, which is strictly speaking,  

212
00:17:00,880 --> 00:17:06,400
not untrue. On a factual level the 
entire global banking industry does,  

213
00:17:06,400 --> 00:17:09,680
in fact, use a lot of total electricity.

214
00:17:09,680 --> 00:17:14,400
But, for scale, it takes six hours of that 
sustained power draw for the Bitcoin network  

215
00:17:14,400 --> 00:17:18,640
to process as many transactions 
as VISA handles in one minute,  

216
00:17:18,640 --> 00:17:25,359
and during that time VISA is using fractions 
of a cent of electricity per transaction.

217
00:17:25,359 --> 00:17:29,680
And that’s just VISA. That’s 
one major institution.

218
00:17:29,680 --> 00:17:35,600
So, like, yes, globally the entirety of the 
banking industry consumes a lot of power,  

219
00:17:35,600 --> 00:17:39,840
and a non-trivial portion of that is 
waste that could be better allocated.  

220
00:17:39,840 --> 00:17:43,920
But it’s also the global banking 
industry for seven billion people,  

221
00:17:43,920 --> 00:17:47,520
and not the hobby horse of a few 
hundred thousand gambling addicts.

222
00:17:47,520 --> 00:17:52,720
So just to head all this off at the pass, 
Bitcoin and proof-of-work cryptocurrency aren’t  

223
00:17:52,720 --> 00:17:57,840
incentivizing a move to green energy sources, 
like solar and wind, they are offsetting it.

224
00:17:57,840 --> 00:18:03,200
Because electrical consumption, electrical 
waste, is the value that underpins Bitcoin.  

225
00:18:03,200 --> 00:18:08,000
Miners spend X dollars in electricity to 
mine a Bitcoin, they expect to be able to  

226
00:18:08,000 --> 00:18:12,960
sell that coin for at least X plus profit. 
When new power sources come online and the  

227
00:18:12,960 --> 00:18:27,840
price of electricity goes down, they don’t 
let X go down, they build a bigger machine.

228
00:18:27,840 --> 00:18:27,963
[Drumming]

229
00:18:27,963 --> 00:18:32,320
In 2012 Vitalik Buterin, a crypto 
enthusiast and butthurt Warlock main  

230
00:18:32,320 --> 00:18:36,640
set out to fix what he saw as the 
failings and inflexibilities of Bitcoin.

231
00:18:36,640 --> 00:18:41,840
Rather than becoming the new digital currency, 
a thing that people actually used to buy stuff,  

232
00:18:41,840 --> 00:18:45,280
Bitcoin had become an unwieldy 
speculative financial instrument,  

233
00:18:45,280 --> 00:18:50,720
too slow and expensive to use for anything 
other than stunt purchases of expensive cars.

234
00:18:50,720 --> 00:18:54,960
It was infested with money 
laundering and mired in bad press.

235
00:18:54,960 --> 00:18:59,600
After the FBI shut down Silk Road you 
couldn’t even buy drugs with it anymore.

236
00:18:59,600 --> 00:19:03,600
In practice you couldn’t do anything 
with your Bitcoin but bet on it,  

237
00:19:03,600 --> 00:19:08,400
lock up money you already have in the hopes 
that Bitcoin goes up later, and pray you don’t  

238
00:19:08,400 --> 00:19:13,520
lose it all in a scam, lose access to your 
wallet, or have it all stolen by an exchange.

239
00:19:13,520 --> 00:19:19,040
The result, launched in 2014, was Ethereum, a 
competing cryptocurrency that boasted lower fees,  

240
00:19:19,040 --> 00:19:22,160
faster transaction times, a 
reduced electrical footprint,  

241
00:19:22,160 --> 00:19:25,920
and, most notably, a sophisticated 
processing functionality.

242
00:19:25,920 --> 00:19:29,840
While the Bitcoin blockchain only tracks 
the location and movement of Bitcoins,  

243
00:19:29,840 --> 00:19:34,480
Ethereum would be broader. In addition to 
tracking Ether coins, the ledger would also  

244
00:19:34,480 --> 00:19:38,640
be able to track arbitrary blocks of data. 
As long as they were compatible with the  

245
00:19:38,640 --> 00:19:42,320
structure of the Ethereum network, 
those blocks of data could even be  

246
00:19:42,320 --> 00:19:47,600
programs that would utilize the validation 
network as a distributed virtual machine.

247
00:19:47,600 --> 00:19:52,080
Vitalik envisioned this as a vast, infinite 
machine, duplicated and distributed across  

248
00:19:52,080 --> 00:19:57,680
thousands or millions of computers, a system onto 
which the entire history of a new internet could  

249
00:19:57,680 --> 00:20:03,120
be immutably written, immune to censorship, 
and impossible for governments to take down.

250
00:20:03,120 --> 00:20:08,240
He saw it dismantling banks and other intermediary 
industries, allowing everyone to be their own  

251
00:20:08,240 --> 00:20:13,360
bank, to be their own stock broker, to bypass 
governments, regulators, and insurance agencies.

252
00:20:13,360 --> 00:20:16,800
His peers envisioned a future 
where Ethereum became not just  

253
00:20:16,800 --> 00:20:22,320
a repository of financial transactions, but 
of identity, with deeds, driver’s licenses,  

254
00:20:22,320 --> 00:20:25,360
professional credentials, medical 
records, educational achievements,  

255
00:20:25,360 --> 00:20:30,880
and employment history turned into tokens and 
stored immutable and eternal on the chain.

256
00:20:30,880 --> 00:20:34,000
Through crypto and the ethereum 
virtual machine they could bring all  

257
00:20:34,000 --> 00:20:36,960
the benefits of Wall Street 
investors and Silicon Valley  

258
00:20:36,960 --> 00:20:41,760
venture capitalists to the poorest people 
of the world, the unbanked and forgotten.

259
00:20:41,760 --> 00:20:45,440
This heady high-minded philosophy 
is outlined in great detail in the  

260
00:20:45,440 --> 00:20:49,760
journalistic abortion The Infinite Machine 
by failed-journalist-turned-crypto-shill  

261
00:20:49,760 --> 00:20:50,640
Camilla Russo.

262
00:20:51,200 --> 00:20:53,440
The book is actually really interesting.

263
00:20:53,440 --> 00:20:58,160
Not for the merits of the writing, Russo fails 
to interrogate the validity or rationality of  

264
00:20:58,160 --> 00:21:02,960
even the simplest claims and falls just 
shy of hagiography by occasionally noting  

265
00:21:02,960 --> 00:21:06,880
that something was a bit tacky or 
embarrassing, but only just shy.

266
00:21:07,440 --> 00:21:11,680
She tells florid stories about the impoverished 
people that Vitalik and friends claimed to be  

267
00:21:11,680 --> 00:21:16,720
working to save, but never once considers that 
the solutions offered might not actually work,  

268
00:21:16,720 --> 00:21:21,200
or that the people claiming to want to solve 
those problems might not even be working on them.

269
00:21:21,200 --> 00:21:25,680
That’s actually a big issue, since the entire 
crypto space, during the entire time that  

270
00:21:25,680 --> 00:21:31,040
Russo’s book covers, was absolutely awash with 
astroturfing schemes where two guys would go to  

271
00:21:31,040 --> 00:21:35,920
some small community in Laos or Angola, take 
a bunch of pictures of people at a “crypto  

272
00:21:35,920 --> 00:21:40,960
investing seminar”, generate some headlines 
for their coin or fund, and then peace out.

273
00:21:40,960 --> 00:21:45,200
For years dudes were going around asking 
vendors if they could slap a Bitcoin  

274
00:21:45,200 --> 00:21:50,160
sticker onto the back of the cash register, 
because the optics of making it look like a  

275
00:21:50,160 --> 00:21:55,600
place takes Bitcoin was cheaper and easier 
than actually using Bitcoin as a currency.

276
00:21:55,600 --> 00:21:59,280
We have an entire decade of 
credulous articles about how  

277
00:21:59,280 --> 00:22:03,600
Venezuela and Chile are on the verge 
of switching entirely to crypto,  

278
00:22:03,600 --> 00:22:08,720
based entirely on the claim of two 
trust fund dudes from San Bernardino.

279
00:22:08,720 --> 00:22:13,360
A whole ten years littered with discarded 
press releases about Dell and Microsoft and  

280
00:22:13,360 --> 00:22:18,800
Square bringing crypto to the consumers 
before just quietly discontinuing their  

281
00:22:18,800 --> 00:22:24,000
services after a year or two when they 
realize the demand isn’t actually there.

282
00:22:24,000 --> 00:22:28,400
The fact that the development of Ethereum was 
extremely dependent on a $100,000 fellowship  

283
00:22:28,400 --> 00:22:32,880
grant from Peter Thiel is mentioned, but the 
ideological implications of that connection  

284
00:22:32,880 --> 00:22:39,280
are never explored, the entire subject occupies 
a single paragraph sprinkled as flavour into a  

285
00:22:39,280 --> 00:22:44,320
story about Vitalik and his co-developers airing 
their grievances about some petty infighting.

286
00:22:44,320 --> 00:22:48,720
The book is mostly useful for it’s value 
as a point of reference against reality.  

287
00:22:48,720 --> 00:22:54,080
It’s a very thorough, if uncritical, 
document of absolutely insane claims.

288
00:22:54,080 --> 00:22:57,280
“The idea was that traits of 
blockchain technology—such  

289
00:22:57,280 --> 00:23:01,680
as having no central point of failure, being 
uncensorable, cutting out intermediaries,  

290
00:23:01,680 --> 00:23:05,920
and being immutable—could also benefit 
other applications besides money.  

291
00:23:05,920 --> 00:23:10,640
Financial instruments like stocks and bonds, and 
commodities like gold, were the obvious targets,  

292
00:23:10,640 --> 00:23:15,440
but people were also talking about putting other 
representations of value like property deeds and  

293
00:23:15,440 --> 00:23:20,720
medical records on the blockchain, too. Those 
efforts—admirable considering Bitcoin hadn’t,  

294
00:23:20,720 --> 00:23:25,600
and still hasn’t, been adopted widely 
as currency—were known as Bitcoin 2.0.”

295
00:23:25,600 --> 00:23:28,400
I love this paragraph because it 
outlines just how disconnected  

296
00:23:28,400 --> 00:23:32,240
from reality the people actually 
building cryptocurrencies really are.

297
00:23:32,240 --> 00:23:36,400
They don’t understand anything about the 
ecosystems they’re trying to disrupt,  

298
00:23:36,400 --> 00:23:40,480
they only know that these are things 
that can be conceptualized as valuable  

299
00:23:40,480 --> 00:23:46,320
and assume that because they understand one very 
complicated thing, programming with cryptography,  

300
00:23:46,320 --> 00:23:51,760
that all other complicated things must 
be lesser in complexity and naturally  

301
00:23:51,760 --> 00:23:57,680
lower in the hierarchy of reality, nails easily 
driven by the hammer that they have created.

302
00:23:57,680 --> 00:24:02,080
The idea of putting medical records on a 
public, decentralized, trustless blockchain  

303
00:24:02,080 --> 00:24:06,320
is absolutely nightmarish, and anyone who 
proposes it should be instantly discredited.

304
00:24:06,320 --> 00:24:10,240
The fact that Russo fails to question 
any of this is journalistic malpractice.

305
00:24:10,800 --> 00:24:15,840
Now, in terms of improvements over 
Bitcoin, Ethereum has many. It’s not hard.

306
00:24:15,840 --> 00:24:17,120
Bitcoin sucks.

307
00:24:17,120 --> 00:24:20,160
In terms of problems with Bitcoin, 
Ethereum solves none of them and  

308
00:24:20,160 --> 00:24:24,080
introduces a whole new suite of problems 
driven by the technofetishistic egotism of  

309
00:24:24,080 --> 00:24:28,160
assuming that programmers are uniquely 
suited to solve society’s problems.

310
00:24:28,160 --> 00:24:32,320
Vitalik wants his invention to be 
an infinite machine, so let’s ask  

311
00:24:32,320 --> 00:24:34,640
what that machine is built to do.

312
00:24:39,080 --> 00:24:40,080
[Drumming]

313
00:24:40,080 --> 00:24:44,320
In order to really understand the full 
scope of this we do need to dig a bit  

314
00:24:44,320 --> 00:24:48,480
more into the technical aspects, 
because that technical functionality  

315
00:24:48,480 --> 00:24:51,200
informs the way the rest of the system behaves.

316
00:24:51,200 --> 00:24:56,240
In a very McLuhanist way, the machine 
shapes the environment around it.

317
00:24:56,240 --> 00:25:00,720
As already mentioned, a blockchain consists 
of two broad fundamental components:  

318
00:25:00,720 --> 00:25:03,440
the ledger and the consensus mechanism.

319
00:25:03,440 --> 00:25:06,960
All currently popular blockchains 
use an append-only ledger.

320
00:25:06,960 --> 00:25:12,240
Now this is, on its own, not that remarkable. 
Append-only is just a database setting that only  

321
00:25:12,240 --> 00:25:17,120
allows new entries to be added to the end of the 
current database, once something is written to the  

322
00:25:17,120 --> 00:25:22,480
database it’s read-only. Standard applications 
are typically things like activity logs,  

323
00:25:22,480 --> 00:25:27,600
which is conceptually all a blockchain 
really is: a giant log of transactions.

324
00:25:27,600 --> 00:25:32,320
The hitch is that it’s decentralized, with 
elective participants hosting a complete copy  

325
00:25:32,320 --> 00:25:39,120
of the entire log, and this is where the second 
component comes in, the consensus mechanism.

326
00:25:39,120 --> 00:25:43,840
All validating participants, called nodes, 
have a complete copy of the database,  

327
00:25:43,840 --> 00:25:47,920
and no one copy is considered 
to be the authoritative copy.

328
00:25:47,920 --> 00:25:52,640
Instead there is a consensus mechanism that 
determines which transactions actually happened.

329
00:25:52,640 --> 00:25:54,960
This is all the proof of work stuff.

330
00:25:54,960 --> 00:25:57,280
Proof of work isn’t the only consensus mechanism,  

331
00:25:57,280 --> 00:26:01,520
but it’s popular because it’s very easy 
to implement by just cloning Bitcoin  

332
00:26:01,520 --> 00:26:05,520
and is resilient against the kinds of 
attacks that crypto enthusiasts care about.

333
00:26:05,520 --> 00:26:07,120
It’s a very brute-force solution,  

334
00:26:07,120 --> 00:26:11,440
but legitimately if you want a network of 
ledgers where no one trusts anyone else,  

335
00:26:11,440 --> 00:26:17,360
just making everyone on the network do extreme 
amounts of wasted, duplicate work is a solution.

336
00:26:17,360 --> 00:26:21,200
One of the major problems that this machine 
solves is what’s called the double-spend  

337
00:26:21,200 --> 00:26:25,760
problem: how do you stop someone 
from spending the same dollar twice?

338
00:26:25,760 --> 00:26:30,080
If someone tries, how do you determine 
which transaction really happened?

339
00:26:30,080 --> 00:26:34,640
Banks solve this problem by not correlating 
account balance with any specific dollar,  

340
00:26:34,640 --> 00:26:39,520
processing transactions first-come-first-serve, 
which they track with central resources,  

341
00:26:39,520 --> 00:26:42,880
and punishing users with overdraft 
fees for double-spending.

342
00:26:42,880 --> 00:26:47,440
Eschewing a central solution, cryptocurrencies 
rely on their consensus mechanism.

343
00:26:47,440 --> 00:26:50,800
The most popular alternative to 
proof-of-work is proof-of-stake,  

344
00:26:50,800 --> 00:26:56,400
where validators post collateral of some kind, 
usually whatever currency is endemic to the chain,  

345
00:26:56,400 --> 00:27:01,120
with the amount of collateral determining their 
odds of being rewarded the validation bounty  

346
00:27:01,120 --> 00:27:06,400
for any given transaction. The main proposal of 
proof of stake is that it significantly reduces  

347
00:27:06,400 --> 00:27:11,200
the wasted power problems of proof of work, 
but it’s less resilient than proof of work.

348
00:27:11,200 --> 00:27:16,320
On the energy cost side of things, proof of stake 
is still inefficient, just by virtue of the sheer  

349
00:27:16,320 --> 00:27:21,920
volume of redundancy, but on a per-user basis 
it’s at least inefficient on the scale of, like,  

350
00:27:22,560 --> 00:27:25,760
an MMO as opposed to a steel foundry.

351
00:27:25,760 --> 00:27:29,920
This is difficult to assess because the 
most popular proof of stake chains are still  

352
00:27:29,920 --> 00:27:34,000
unpopular and low traffic in the 
scope of things, heavily centralized.  

353
00:27:34,000 --> 00:27:38,240
Claims about scalability are backed 
up by nothing but the creators’ word.

354
00:27:38,240 --> 00:27:42,160
Proof of stake is also significantly more 
complex because there now needs to be some  

355
00:27:42,160 --> 00:27:46,560
mechanism for determining who gets to do the 
validations, and also determining how audits  

356
00:27:46,560 --> 00:27:49,760
are conducted, and then the question 
of who has control over that system,  

357
00:27:49,760 --> 00:27:54,000
and whether or not someone can gain control of 
that system or control over the whole stake,  

358
00:27:54,000 --> 00:27:57,840
via just buying out the staking 
pool, et cetera et cetera et cetera.

359
00:27:57,840 --> 00:28:02,000
Proof of Stake also, even more explicitly, 
rewards the wealthy who have the capital  

360
00:28:02,000 --> 00:28:07,600
to both stake and spend. It’s also even more 
explicitly exclusionary. Ethereum’s proposed  

361
00:28:07,600 --> 00:28:13,760
proof-of-stake migration has a buy-in of 32 Ether, 
which at the time of writing is about $130,000,  

362
00:28:14,560 --> 00:28:18,160
so really only early adopters 
and the wealthy can actually  

363
00:28:18,160 --> 00:28:21,200
meaningfully participate 
for more than just crumbs.

364
00:28:21,200 --> 00:28:25,680
This is, in turn, compounding inherent problems 
with the long term growth of the chain.  

365
00:28:25,680 --> 00:28:29,280
Even if you solve the escalating 
power requirements of proof of work,  

366
00:28:29,280 --> 00:28:34,240
the data requirements of storing the chain 
and participating as a validator are also  

367
00:28:34,240 --> 00:28:39,680
prohibitive in a way that inevitably centralizes 
power in the hands of a few wealthy operators.

368
00:28:39,680 --> 00:28:43,920
Vitalik: 85 terabytes per year is 
actually fine, right? Like, because, uh,  

369
00:28:43,920 --> 00:28:48,560
85 terabytes per year, like, if you have, if 
you have even one person that just keeps buying,  

370
00:28:48,560 --> 00:28:51,920
like, um, a hundred dollar hard drive, like, uh, 
I think once every month then they can store it,  

371
00:28:51,920 --> 00:28:55,840
right, like it’s something like that. So, it’s 
too big for just like a casual user that just  

372
00:28:55,840 --> 00:29:00,400
wants to run the chain on their laptop, but one 
dedicated user who cares, they can totally afford  

373
00:29:00,400 --> 00:29:04,080
to, uh, afford to store the chain. And so 85 
terabytes, not a big deal, right, but once you  

374
00:29:04,080 --> 00:29:08,320
crank that number higher there comes a point 
at which it starts becoming a really big deal.

375
00:29:08,320 --> 00:29:12,720
The major downside of all these systems is 
that they’re extremely slow. Proof of work  

376
00:29:12,720 --> 00:29:16,560
is inefficient by design, and proof of stake 
has multiple layers of lottery that need to  

377
00:29:16,560 --> 00:29:21,520
be executed before any transaction can 
be conducted, and in particular suffers  

378
00:29:21,520 --> 00:29:26,000
from delays when elected validators are 
offline and the system needs to draw again.

379
00:29:26,000 --> 00:29:28,800
As an extension of being slow 
they’re also prone to getting  

380
00:29:28,800 --> 00:29:32,720
overwhelmed if too many people try 
to make transactions simultaneously,  

381
00:29:32,720 --> 00:29:37,200
which can cause de-syncs between validators 
and even lead to what’s called a fork,  

382
00:29:37,200 --> 00:29:42,320
where two or more pools of validators reach a 
different consensus about the state of the network  

383
00:29:42,320 --> 00:29:48,320
and each branch keeps on going afterwards 
assuming that it is the authoritative version.

384
00:29:48,320 --> 00:29:54,320
Forks can also be caused on purpose, and this 
is, in fact, the only way to effectively undo  

385
00:29:54,320 --> 00:29:59,520
transactions. Like if someone stole your 
coins the only way to get them back would  

386
00:29:59,520 --> 00:30:04,240
be to convince the people who manage the 
chain itself to negotiate a rollback.

387
00:30:05,120 --> 00:30:07,200
That’s foreshadowing for later.

388
00:30:07,200 --> 00:30:10,960
Now, because the nature of a fork involves 
a disagreement on what transactions  

389
00:30:10,960 --> 00:30:16,000
actually happened, and who got paid for those 
transactions, this means that each arm of the  

390
00:30:16,000 --> 00:30:22,080
fork has a vested interest in its own arm being 
the authoritative arm, so resolving forks can turn  

391
00:30:22,080 --> 00:30:28,800
into irreconcilable schisms, which is funny as 
an outside observer viewing it as inane internet  

392
00:30:28,800 --> 00:30:34,000
drama, but is frankly unacceptable for anything 
posturing as a serious and legitimate currency.

393
00:30:34,000 --> 00:30:37,040
Like, it’s important to stress that 
because of the nature of the chain,  

394
00:30:37,040 --> 00:30:43,440
the way that the ID numbers of later blocks are 
dependent on the outcomes of previous blocks,  

395
00:30:43,440 --> 00:30:48,400
these aren’t just a few disputed transactions 
that need to be resolved between the buyer,  

396
00:30:48,400 --> 00:30:53,120
the seller, and the payment processor, 
these are disagreements on the fundamental  

397
00:30:53,120 --> 00:30:58,960
state of the entire economy that 
create an entire alternate reality.

398
00:30:58,960 --> 00:31:02,960
It’s an ecosystem that absolutely 
demolishes consumer protections  

399
00:31:02,960 --> 00:31:06,960
and makes the re-implementation 
of them extremely difficult.

400
00:31:06,960 --> 00:31:10,960
One of the big selling points of all this 
technology is that it’s particularly secure,  

401
00:31:10,960 --> 00:31:15,200
very difficult for anyone to hack it 
directly, since there’s so much redundancy.

402
00:31:15,200 --> 00:31:18,800
A lot of hay is made about the system’s 
resiliency against man-in-the-middle  

403
00:31:18,800 --> 00:31:22,240
attacks, which are your classic 
Hollywood hacker type attacks.

404
00:31:22,240 --> 00:31:27,360
Someone sends a command from point A and on the 
way to point B it is intercepted and altered.  

405
00:31:27,360 --> 00:31:32,880
Someone hacks into the bank and adds an arbitrary 
number of zeroes onto their account balance.

406
00:31:32,880 --> 00:31:35,920
Evangelists will commonly claim 
that blockchain could revolutionize  

407
00:31:35,920 --> 00:31:38,480
the global shipping industry and reduce fraud.

408
00:31:38,480 --> 00:31:40,320
It’s a good claim to interrogate.

409
00:31:40,320 --> 00:31:43,600
First, the things that blockchain is 
capable of tracking are things that  

410
00:31:43,600 --> 00:31:48,320
manufacturers and shippers are already 
tracking, or at least trying to track,  

411
00:31:48,320 --> 00:31:52,880
so this is not so much “revolution” 
as it would be “standardization.”

412
00:31:52,880 --> 00:31:57,440
Even that is built on a predicate assumption 
that everyone picks the same chain.

413
00:31:57,440 --> 00:32:00,160
It’s an extremely optimistic assumption.

414
00:32:00,160 --> 00:32:03,040
Many, many, many firms deliberately want their  

415
00:32:03,040 --> 00:32:07,360
information centralized and obfuscated 
to protect against corporate espionage.

416
00:32:07,360 --> 00:32:11,680
The lack of a shared, standardized 
bucket to put all the information into  

417
00:32:11,680 --> 00:32:16,480
is not because it’s been heretofore 
impossible, but because it’s been undesirable.

418
00:32:16,480 --> 00:32:21,600
Second, it assumes the existence of a theoretical 
mechanism that ensures the synchronization of the  

419
00:32:21,600 --> 00:32:26,800
chain and reality above and beyond the 
current capacity of logistics software,  

420
00:32:26,800 --> 00:32:29,840
some means of preventing people from just  

421
00:32:29,840 --> 00:32:35,360
lying to the blockchain and giving it the 
information it expects to be receiving,  

422
00:32:35,360 --> 00:32:40,640
the blockchain equivalent of ripping off the 
shipping label and slapping it on the new box.

423
00:32:40,640 --> 00:32:43,360
The bigger problem here is 
that in the pantheon of fraud,  

424
00:32:43,360 --> 00:32:46,240
man-in-the-middle attacks 
are actually pretty rare.

425
00:32:46,240 --> 00:32:51,040
Global shipping needs to deal with it in certain 
capacities, but taken on the whole the vast  

426
00:32:51,040 --> 00:32:55,440
majority of fraud doesn’t come from altering 
information as it passes between parties,  

427
00:32:55,440 --> 00:32:59,840
rather from colluding parties 
entering bad information at the start.

428
00:32:59,840 --> 00:33:04,080
Con artists don’t hack the Gibson to transfer 
your funds to their offshore accounts,  

429
00:33:04,080 --> 00:33:06,400
they convince you to give them your password.

430
00:33:06,400 --> 00:33:12,560
Most fraud comes from people who technically 
have permission to be doing what they’re doing.

431
00:33:12,560 --> 00:33:15,200
Rather than preventing these 
actual common types of fraud,  

432
00:33:15,200 --> 00:33:19,440
cryptocurrency has made them absurdly easy, 
and the main reason why cryptocurrency needs  

433
00:33:19,440 --> 00:33:23,360
to be so resistant to man-in-the-middle 
attacks is because the decentralized nature  

434
00:33:23,360 --> 00:33:27,840
of the network otherwise makes them 
acutely vulnerable to those attacks.

435
00:33:27,840 --> 00:33:30,560
What this all kinda means 
is that blockchains are all  

436
00:33:30,560 --> 00:33:34,000
pretty bad at doing most of the things 
they’re trying to do, and a lot of the  

437
00:33:34,000 --> 00:33:39,440
innovations in blockchains are attempts at 
solving problems that blockchains introduced.

438
00:33:39,440 --> 00:33:43,840
The biggest issue that cryptocurrencies have 
suffered from is a lack of tangible things to  

439
00:33:43,840 --> 00:33:50,080
actually use them on as currencies, rent or food 
or transit, and this is for pretty simple reasons.

440
00:33:50,080 --> 00:33:54,400
One is that the transaction fees on popular 
chains are so prohibitive that it’s pointless  

441
00:33:54,400 --> 00:33:58,480
to use them on any transaction that isn’t 
hundreds, if not thousands of dollars;  

442
00:33:58,480 --> 00:34:04,480
no one is going to buy the Bitcoin Bucket from 
their local KFC. Ethereum’s main transaction fee,  

443
00:34:04,480 --> 00:34:11,520
called Gas, on a good day runs around $20 US 
per transaction, but that’s severely optimistic.

444
00:34:11,520 --> 00:34:16,320
As of December 2021 the daily average 
cost of Gas hasn’t gone below $50  

445
00:34:16,320 --> 00:34:20,960
US since August, with the three 
month daily average riding over $130.

446
00:34:21,920 --> 00:34:24,480
And that’s just the daily average.

447
00:34:24,480 --> 00:34:28,880
The hourly price can, and does, swing 
by up to two orders of magnitude.

448
00:34:28,880 --> 00:34:32,159
The throughput of blockchains is 
so abysmal that transaction slots  

449
00:34:32,159 --> 00:34:36,079
are auctioned off to the highest bidder, 
that’s why these numbers are so extreme.

450
00:34:36,080 --> 00:34:40,719
It only takes a few high rollers competing on 
a transaction to drive the hourly price of gas  

451
00:34:40,719 --> 00:34:47,839
up over $1000 US. The internal term for this 
is a “gas war” because it’s just that common.

452
00:34:47,840 --> 00:34:51,280
Bots, in particular, can drive 
gas prices well into the tens  

453
00:34:51,280 --> 00:34:54,400
of thousands of dollars as they 
compete to capitalize on mistakes,  

454
00:34:54,400 --> 00:34:58,480
such as someone listing something for 
sale well below its general market price.

455
00:34:58,480 --> 00:35:04,400
Also, it needs to be stressed: these gas wars 
aren’t localized to just the thing that’s being  

456
00:35:04,400 --> 00:35:10,080
fought over. If Steam is getting hammered because 
ConcernedApe posted Stardew Valley 2 by surprise,  

457
00:35:10,080 --> 00:35:13,760
that will probably stay pretty well 
contained. If Taylor Swift concert  

458
00:35:13,760 --> 00:35:18,000
tickets go on sale and LiveNation gets 
crushed, you might never even know.

459
00:35:18,000 --> 00:35:22,400
What those don’t do is cause 
the cost of placing an order  

460
00:35:22,400 --> 00:35:26,960
on DriveThruRPG to spike by eight 
thousand percent for three hours.

461
00:35:26,960 --> 00:35:31,040
The second big reason is that value on 
the coins themselves is so volatile that  

462
00:35:31,040 --> 00:35:34,400
unless you’re willing to engage with 
the speculative nature of the coins  

463
00:35:34,400 --> 00:35:38,400
there’s actually a huge risk in 
accepting them as payment for anything.

464
00:35:38,400 --> 00:35:42,880
Bitcoin in particular, owing to its glacial 
transaction times, suffers from problems where  

465
00:35:42,880 --> 00:35:47,760
the value of the coin can change dramatically 
between the start and end of a transaction.

466
00:35:47,760 --> 00:35:52,560
This is such a problem that it’s led to the rise 
of an entire strata of middlemen in the ecosystem,  

467
00:35:52,560 --> 00:35:56,320
so-called “stablecoin” exchanges 
like Tether that exist to quickly  

468
00:35:56,320 --> 00:36:00,160
transfer cryptocurrencies between 
each other and lock-in values.

469
00:36:00,160 --> 00:36:02,960
The stablecoins, rather than 
having a speculative value,  

470
00:36:02,960 --> 00:36:07,520
have a value that’s pegged to the value of an 
actual currency, like the Euro or US dollar.

471
00:36:07,520 --> 00:36:11,360
The underlying problem that they 
exist to solve is itself twofold.

472
00:36:11,360 --> 00:36:13,440
One is that converting cryptocurrency into  

473
00:36:13,440 --> 00:36:16,880
dollars is the step of the process that 
makes you accountable to the tax man,  

474
00:36:16,880 --> 00:36:21,760
and the primary goal of crypto in general is 
to starve public services, so that’s a no go.

475
00:36:21,760 --> 00:36:25,440
The second is that there just 
aren’t actually that many buyers,  

476
00:36:25,440 --> 00:36:30,160
and there’s not enough liquidity in 
the ecosystem to cash out big holdings.

477
00:36:30,160 --> 00:36:33,840
Tether, the largest stablecoin, used 
to advertise itself as being backed  

478
00:36:33,840 --> 00:36:37,920
on a one to one basis back when it was 
called Realcoin, but that language has  

479
00:36:37,920 --> 00:36:42,560
become far more nebulous over time as it’s 
become obvious that it just isn’t true.

480
00:36:42,560 --> 00:36:47,280
This is a very complicated situation, but the 
short version is that the people who own Tether  

481
00:36:47,280 --> 00:36:52,240
also own a real money exchange called Bitfinex, 
and there’s evidence that the two services,  

482
00:36:52,240 --> 00:36:56,320
both which require having actual dollars 
on hand in order to back their products and  

483
00:36:56,320 --> 00:37:01,760
facilitate exchanges, are sharing the same pool 
of money, swapping it back and forth as needed.

484
00:37:01,760 --> 00:37:06,000
This means that at any given time 
either service is potentially backed by  

485
00:37:06,000 --> 00:37:10,240
zero dollars, or at least that’s what 
the data implies might be the case.

486
00:37:10,800 --> 00:37:13,840
Point is that if you’re a high 
roller with tens of millions  

487
00:37:13,840 --> 00:37:16,480
of conceptual dollars tied up in cryptocurrency,  

488
00:37:16,480 --> 00:37:21,040
there’s a fundamental cash problem. Your 
holdings have inflated to tens, hundreds,  

489
00:37:21,040 --> 00:37:27,040
or thousands of times what you put in, but that 
price is just theoretical. It’s speculative.

490
00:37:27,040 --> 00:37:30,480
You have all this crypto, you 
can’t meaningfully spend it,  

491
00:37:30,480 --> 00:37:33,360
and there’s not enough 
buyers for you to get it out.

492
00:37:33,360 --> 00:37:39,120
In order for you to cash out you need 
to convince someone else to buy in.

493
00:37:39,120 --> 00:37:44,320
These factors, taken holistically, mean 
that cryptocurrency is a Bigger Fool scam.  

494
00:37:44,320 --> 00:37:49,040
There’s a lot of digital ink spilt trying 
to outline if it’s a decentralized Ponzi  

495
00:37:49,040 --> 00:37:54,080
scheme or a pyramid scheme or some hybrid 
of the two, which is a taxonomical argument  

496
00:37:54,080 --> 00:37:58,880
that I’m not here to settle, but, like 
both of those, it’s a Bigger Fool scam.

497
00:37:58,880 --> 00:38:02,240
The whole thing operates by buying 
worthless assets believing that you  

498
00:38:02,240 --> 00:38:05,360
will later be able to sell them to a bigger fool.

499
00:38:05,360 --> 00:38:09,120
The entire structure of cryptocurrencies 
at their basic level of operation  

500
00:38:09,120 --> 00:38:13,520
is designed to deliver the greatest rewards 
to the earliest adopters, regardless of  

501
00:38:13,520 --> 00:38:18,400
if you’re talking about proof-of-work or 
proof-of-stake. This is inherent to their being.

502
00:38:18,400 --> 00:38:20,080
As Stephen Diel put it

503
00:38:20,080 --> 00:38:24,960
“These schemes around crypto tokens cannot create 
or destroy actual dollars, they can only shift  

504
00:38:24,960 --> 00:38:30,000
them around. If you sell your crypto and make a 
profit in dollars, it’s only because someone else  

505
00:38:30,000 --> 00:38:35,200
bought it at a higher price than you did. And 
then they expect to do the same and so on and  

506
00:38:35,200 --> 00:38:41,360
so on ad infinitum. Every dollar that comes out of 
cryptocurrency needs to come from a later investor  

507
00:38:41,360 --> 00:38:46,080
putting a dollar in. Crypto investments 
cannot be anything but a zero sum game,  

508
00:38:46,080 --> 00:38:51,360
and many are actually massively negative sum. In 
order to presume a crypto investment functions as  

509
00:38:51,360 --> 00:38:56,800
a store of value we simultaneously need to 
suppose an infinite chain of greater fools  

510
00:38:56,800 --> 00:39:01,680
who keep buying these assets at any 
irrational price and into the future forever.”

