00:45:26,000 --> 00:45:30,240
art that’s difficult to monetize via 
conventional channels like physical prints,  

602
00:45:30,240 --> 00:45:34,400
raced into the space and, on 
the whole, lost a lot of money.

603
00:45:34,400 --> 00:45:38,000
Critics began questioning what it was 
that was actually being bought and sold.

604
00:45:38,000 --> 00:45:42,320
Copyright? Commercial permissions? 
A digital file? Bragging rights?

605
00:45:42,320 --> 00:45:46,480
In a huge number of cases the answer 
wasn’t very clear, and even the sellers,  

606
00:45:46,480 --> 00:45:51,760
caught in the promise of a payday, weren’t 
altogether sure what they had even sold.

607
00:45:51,760 --> 00:45:56,480
Tons of the tokens did little more than point to 
images stored on normal servers readily accessible  

608
00:45:56,480 --> 00:46:02,400
via HTTP, meaning the bought assets would be 
just as vulnerable to link rot as anything else.

609
00:46:02,400 --> 00:46:09,600
Some pointed to images stored on peer-to-peer IPFS 
servers, which are more resistant to link rot as,  

610
00:46:09,600 --> 00:46:14,720
similar to a torrent, it only requires that 
someone keep the file active somewhere,  

611
00:46:14,720 --> 00:46:20,080
rather than requiring the original server to 
stay up, but as millions of dead torrents prove:  

612
00:46:20,080 --> 00:46:24,960
that’s still a far cry from the “eternal” 
storage solution that evangelists were claiming.

613
00:46:24,960 --> 00:46:29,040
The images were stored and delivered the 
same way as any other image on the internet,  

614
00:46:29,040 --> 00:46:32,960
easily saved or duplicated simply 
by virtue of the fact that in order  

615
00:46:32,960 --> 00:46:36,640
for your computer to display an 
image it needs to download it.

616
00:46:36,640 --> 00:46:43,280
Claims of digital scarcity apply only to the 
token itself, not the thing the token signified.

617
00:46:43,280 --> 00:46:47,760
More than that, there was no cryptographic 
relationship between the images and the tokens.

618
00:46:47,760 --> 00:46:52,000
The image associated with a token 
could be easily altered or replaced  

619
00:46:52,000 --> 00:46:57,840
if the person with access to the server that 
the image was hosted on just changed file names,  

620
00:46:57,840 --> 00:47:03,040
making the relationship between the two tenuous 
and flimsy in a way that undermined the claims  

621
00:47:03,040 --> 00:47:08,880
that this was somehow a more durable, 
reliable way of transacting digital art.

622
00:47:08,880 --> 00:47:12,160
There was also no root proof of authenticity, no  

623
00:47:12,160 --> 00:47:16,880
confirmation that the person minting the 
artwork was the person who created the artwork.

624
00:47:16,880 --> 00:47:21,680
This is a pretty handy encapsulation of the 
way that blockchain fails to solve the most  

625
00:47:21,680 --> 00:47:28,160
common problems with fraud, which tend to start 
with bad data going into a system at the input,  

626
00:47:28,160 --> 00:47:31,120
not data being altered mid-stream.

627
00:47:31,120 --> 00:47:33,920
Artists who complained about 
this system which clearly  

628
00:47:33,920 --> 00:47:38,480
incentivized impersonating popular 
artists, including deceased artists,  

629
00:47:38,480 --> 00:47:42,720
were told that it was their fault for 
not jumping in sooner, that if they had  

630
00:47:42,720 --> 00:47:48,160
bought in and minted their stuff first then 
it would be easy to prove the forgeries.

631
00:47:48,160 --> 00:47:52,000
Because evangelists don’t see this as 
a tool, as a market that may or may  

632
00:47:52,000 --> 00:47:55,120
not fit into an artist’s business, they see it as  

633
00:47:55,120 --> 00:48:00,160
the future, so failure to participate isn’t 
a business decision, it’s just a mistake.

634
00:48:00,720 --> 00:48:02,080
They’re terrible people.

635
00:48:02,080 --> 00:48:04,080
All told the frenzy collapsed pretty quickly.

636
00:48:04,080 --> 00:48:06,960
By June the market had 
already receded by about 90%,  

637
00:48:07,600 --> 00:48:12,160
which, incidentally, just further incentivized 
the low-effort process of minting other peoples’  

638
00:48:12,160 --> 00:48:17,280
artwork, to the point that art platform Deviant 
Art implemented an extremely well received feature  

639
00:48:17,280 --> 00:48:21,120
that scans several popular NFT 
marketplaces for matching images.

640
00:48:21,760 --> 00:48:24,480
The output of that is extremely depressing.

641
00:48:25,040 --> 00:48:29,520
Not to labour this point, but reposting 
digital art without attribution is nothing new.

642
00:48:29,520 --> 00:48:32,560
Profiting off someone else's 
art is also nothing new.

643
00:48:32,560 --> 00:48:36,080
All that’s new is NFTs represent 
a high-energy marketplace with an  

644
00:48:36,080 --> 00:48:40,880
irrational pricing culture where the mean buyer is 
easily flattered and not particularly discerning.

645
00:48:40,880 --> 00:48:45,600
The potential payoff is extremely high, much, 
much higher than a bootleg Redbubble store,  

646
00:48:45,600 --> 00:48:50,400
the consequences border nonexistent, and 
the market is clearly in an untenable state,  

647
00:48:50,400 --> 00:48:55,040
so there’s an incentive to get in at as 
low a cost as possible before it collapses,  

648
00:48:55,040 --> 00:48:57,200
hence the absolute plague of art theft.

649
00:48:57,200 --> 00:48:59,840
Even the argument that artists 
could make passive revenue off  

650
00:48:59,840 --> 00:49:02,880
secondary sales turned out to 
have a lot of caveats attached.

651
00:49:02,880 --> 00:49:06,880
One, the smart contract for the token needs 
to have a function that defines royalties,  

652
00:49:06,880 --> 00:49:10,560
so anyone who minted a token based 
off of hype making it sound like an  

653
00:49:10,560 --> 00:49:13,120
inherent function of the system was out of luck.

654
00:49:13,120 --> 00:49:18,800
And, two, the token doesn’t know what a sale 
is and can’t differentiate between being sold  

655
00:49:18,800 --> 00:49:23,920
and being transferred, so it’s actually 
the marketplace that informs the token  

656
00:49:23,920 --> 00:49:26,800
“you’re being sold” and collects the royalties.

657
00:49:26,800 --> 00:49:31,040
End result, royalties are easily bypassed 
simply by using a marketplace that doesn’t  

658
00:49:31,040 --> 00:49:34,560
collect royalties or uses a different 
format of royalty collection that’s  

659
00:49:34,560 --> 00:49:37,040
incompatible with the function the token uses.

660
00:49:37,040 --> 00:49:41,360
While a few sellers, legitimate and otherwise, 
made off with undeniably big paydays,  

661
00:49:41,360 --> 00:49:45,280
hundreds of thousands of artists bought 
in only to find that there wasn’t a new,  

662
00:49:45,280 --> 00:49:48,720
revolutionary, highly trafficked 
audience of digital art collectors.

663
00:49:48,720 --> 00:49:53,120
Instead there was a closed market dealing in 
casino chips where the primary winners were  

664
00:49:53,120 --> 00:49:57,680
those already connected, who already had the means 
to get the attention of the whales and the media,  

665
00:49:57,680 --> 00:50:02,800
a market where participation required buying 
into a cryptocurrency at a rapidly fluctuating  

666
00:50:02,800 --> 00:50:07,440
price in order to pay the minting costs to 
post the work, where it would sit, unsold.

667
00:50:07,440 --> 00:50:10,800
This left those artists in the lurch, 
where they had to choose between just  

668
00:50:10,800 --> 00:50:15,440
eating the losses, or attempting to convince 
their existing audience to buy-in as well.

669
00:50:15,440 --> 00:50:19,680
The people who actually won were the people 
with large holdings of cryptocurrency,  

670
00:50:19,680 --> 00:50:24,240
specifically Ethereum which mediated the 
vast majority of these big ticket purchases.

671
00:50:24,240 --> 00:50:27,120
David Gerrard, author of Attack 
of the 50 Foot Blockchain,  

672
00:50:27,120 --> 00:50:30,160
summarized it on his blog very succinctly as such:

673
00:50:30,160 --> 00:50:34,800
“NFTs are entirely for the benefit of the crypto 
grifters. The only purpose the artists serve  

674
00:50:34,800 --> 00:50:38,560
is as aspiring suckers to pump the 
concept of crypto — and, of course,  

675
00:50:38,560 --> 00:50:41,600
to buy cryptocurrency to pay for ‘minting’ NFTs.  

676
00:50:41,600 --> 00:50:45,360
Sometimes the artist gets some crumbs to 
keep them pumping the concept of crypto.”

677
00:50:45,360 --> 00:50:50,240
The rush benefits them in two ways: first 
the price of Ether itself goes up directly  

678
00:50:50,240 --> 00:50:55,360
from the spike in demand, between January and 
May the price of Ether rose from $700 to $4000,  

679
00:50:56,480 --> 00:51:00,880
and second there’s new actual buyers 
who aren’t just trading Bitcoin for  

680
00:51:00,880 --> 00:51:04,320
tether for ether and back again, 
but are buying in with dollars,  

681
00:51:04,320 --> 00:51:09,120
providing the whole system with the liquidity 
needed for whales to actually cash out.

682
00:51:09,120 --> 00:51:13,840
This arrangement, needing to buy a highly 
volatile coin from people who paid far,  

683
00:51:13,840 --> 00:51:17,680
far less for it in order to participate 
in a market that they control,  

684
00:51:17,680 --> 00:51:20,960
is why people reflexively describe 
the whole arrangement as a scam.

685
00:51:20,960 --> 00:51:26,240
If you buy in at $4000 and compete against 
people who bought in at $4, you’re the sucker.

686
00:51:26,240 --> 00:51:30,320
It reveals the basic truth that these 
aren’t marketplaces, they’re casinos.

687
00:51:30,320 --> 00:51:32,400
And, indeed, even through all the rhetoric  

688
00:51:32,400 --> 00:51:36,480
of “protecting artists” and whatnot was 
the ever-present spectre of the gamble:  

689
00:51:36,480 --> 00:51:40,400
whatever you buy now might be 
worth hundreds of times more later.

690
00:51:40,400 --> 00:51:44,240
Constantly invoked is the opposite 
proposition of the bad deal:  

691
00:51:44,240 --> 00:51:47,600
what if you had been the 
person who bought in at $4?

692
00:51:48,560 --> 00:51:53,120
Let’s take a closer look at that eye 
watering $69 million Beeple sale.

693
00:51:54,000 --> 00:51:58,480
Independent journalist Amy Castor has done an 
enviable job running down the details here in  

694
00:51:58,480 --> 00:52:04,560
her piece “Metakovan, the mystery Beeple art 
buyer, and his NFT/DeFi scheme“ but to summarize  

695
00:52:04,560 --> 00:52:08,560
the long and short of her notes, the buyer is 
a crypto entrepreneur named Vignesh Sundaresan  

696
00:52:08,560 --> 00:52:13,120
who purchased the piece to boost the reputation 
and value of his own crypto investment scheme  

697
00:52:13,120 --> 00:52:19,760
Metapurse and Metapurse’s own token B.20, 
which Beeple owns 2% of the total supply of.

698
00:52:19,760 --> 00:52:26,240
Following the Christie's sale the reported 
value of B.20 went from 36¢ per token to $23.

699
00:52:27,280 --> 00:52:29,600
And that’s just the anatomy of a single sale.

700
00:52:29,600 --> 00:52:35,040
The very obvious conclusion observers reached 
was that none of this is about the art at all,  

701
00:52:35,040 --> 00:52:38,400
but the speculative value; 
not what it’s worth to you,  

702
00:52:38,400 --> 00:52:41,840
but what it’ll potentially be worth 
in the future to someone else.

703
00:52:41,840 --> 00:52:46,160
It’s not a market, it’s a casino, gambling on the 
receipt for an image or video that’s otherwise  

704
00:52:46,160 --> 00:52:47,840
infinitely digitally replicable.

705
00:52:47,840 --> 00:52:52,720
The thing itself is immaterial as 
long as it can make a line go up.

706
00:52:52,720 --> 00:52:56,720
This is the essence of the market, 
and a microcosm of what evangelists  

707
00:52:56,720 --> 00:53:01,440
imagine they want to see as the future, 
the financialization of everything.

708
00:53:01,440 --> 00:53:04,800
The frenzied market around old Reddit 
memes was doomed from the start.  

709
00:53:04,800 --> 00:53:09,440
There’s a finite supply of meaningful 
originals, so to keep this thing going,  

710
00:53:09,440 --> 00:53:17,040
to keep the line going up, you need something 
more, something less tied to anything specific.

711
00:53:23,320 --> 00:53:24,320
--

712
00:53:24,320 --> 00:53:27,920
In the months since the initial 
craze the marketplace had mutated.

713
00:53:27,920 --> 00:53:31,680
The It Thing was no longer memes or 
digital works from established artists,  

714
00:53:31,680 --> 00:53:36,960
but character profiles from large, procedurally 
generated collections with names like CryptoPunks,  

715
00:53:36,960 --> 00:53:41,040
Bored Ape Yacht Club, Lazy Lions, 
Cool Cats, Ether Gals, Gator World,  

716
00:53:41,040 --> 00:53:45,680
Baby Llama Club, Magic Mushroom Club, 
Rogue Society Bot, and Crypto Chicks.

717
00:53:45,680 --> 00:53:51,200
These were notable for, again, commanding utterly 
irrational prices seemingly completely decoupled  

718
00:53:51,200 --> 00:53:57,440
from any legitimate or legal transaction, 
and being generally extremely fugly.

719
00:53:57,440 --> 00:54:01,600
This surge generated an immediately 
adversarial relationship between the buyers,  

720
00:54:01,600 --> 00:54:05,440
who touted them as both evidence 
of their extravagant wealth and  

721
00:54:05,440 --> 00:54:11,200
their foresight into the future of digital 
economies, and pretty much everyone else.

722
00:54:11,200 --> 00:54:16,160
A very common response to anyone using one of 
these profile pics, or bragging about their  

723
00:54:16,160 --> 00:54:21,840
purchase, became saving and reposting the image 
in reply, or even changing profile pics to match.

724
00:54:22,400 --> 00:54:25,760
Spurred by a speculative tweet from 
Twitter developers suggesting that  

725
00:54:25,760 --> 00:54:30,400
they were working on an NFT verification 
system, Twitter users broadly rallied at the  

726
00:54:30,400 --> 00:54:34,480
opportunity to immediately identify 
people that it was okay to bully.

727
00:54:34,480 --> 00:54:38,720
Tweets from within the cryptosphere started 
leaking out, things like Santiago Santos  

728
00:54:38,720 --> 00:54:45,840
tweeting things like “NFTs = Identity 2.0. Can’t 
remember the last time I used my pic on the left.”

729
00:54:45,840 --> 00:54:50,800
Emphasis on physical traits. Genetic 
lottery. Prone to bias and prejudice.

730
00:54:50,800 --> 00:54:56,240
Identity by choice. Unique and digitally 
scarce. Representation of values and beliefs.

731
00:54:56,800 --> 00:55:01,840
Of course what Santiago was leaving out was 
that he had paid the equivalent of $171,000  

732
00:55:02,560 --> 00:55:09,520
US for that profile pic, which probably gives him 
some incentive to really commit to it as something  

733
00:55:09,520 --> 00:55:13,520
interesting and special, even 
though, stripped to the studs,  

734
00:55:14,240 --> 00:55:20,080
literally all he was describing was using a 
non-representational image as a profile pic.

735
00:55:20,080 --> 00:55:26,240
For about six years my profile pic on the Dungeons 
and Dragons forums was a stock photo of a cabbage.

736
00:55:26,800 --> 00:55:30,800
So, not really breaking new ground here.

737
00:55:30,800 --> 00:55:34,880
Greg Isenberg sat at his computer and 
decided to bang out “most people who  

738
00:55:34,880 --> 00:55:37,600
make fun of NFTs
- Own zero NFTs 

739
00:55:37,600 --> 00:55:41,520
- Have never minted an NFT
- Have never participated in a community 

740
00:55:41,520 --> 00:55:45,840
- Have never staked their NFT
- Haven’t built on-top of an NFT project 

741
00:55:45,840 --> 00:55:51,520
- Have never earned an NFT playing a game
- Missed out on BAYC, Punks, Cool Cats etc.”

742
00:55:51,520 --> 00:55:56,320
A chain of logic implying that skeptics of 
the market are just uninformed sore losers.

743
00:55:56,320 --> 00:55:59,760
Incidents like these lent to the very 
accurate perception that the loudest  

744
00:55:59,760 --> 00:56:03,440
voices in NFTs weren’t very familiar 
with internet culture as a whole,  

745
00:56:03,440 --> 00:56:08,720
weren’t terribly smart in general, and were by and 
large coming at all this from the financial side,  

746
00:56:08,720 --> 00:56:13,920
further supported by all of them having “tweets 
are not investment advice” in their twitter bios.

747
00:56:13,920 --> 00:56:22,160
In short the same people 
who made and bought Juicero.

748
00:56:22,720 --> 00:56:26,080
It also laid bare that the 
conversations were inherently suspect.

749
00:56:26,080 --> 00:56:30,000
How can you ever trust the sincerity 
of someone telling you how awesome  

750
00:56:30,000 --> 00:56:37,360
their $171,000 investment is when your 
persuasion stands to directly benefit them  

751
00:56:37,360 --> 00:56:41,120
by potentially driving up the value 
of their investment portfolio?

752
00:56:41,120 --> 00:56:48,480
You’ve gotta be extremely rich for 
$171,000 to not be an extremely sunk cost,  

753
00:56:48,480 --> 00:56:53,760
and that’s absolutely going to weigh on your 
mind and influence how you see the market.

754
00:56:53,760 --> 00:56:57,600
So for my part I tweeted about several 
of these incidents and was, in response,  

755
