a pretty expensive system, but also a very 
potent anxiety about their financial future.

798
01:00:07,600 --> 01:00:10,080
It goes without saying that 
they’re fixated on money,  

799
01:00:10,080 --> 01:00:14,080
and they principally understand the 
technology as a means of making money.

800
01:00:14,080 --> 01:00:19,600
Criticism of the system is typically met 
with confusion. Don’t you want to make money?

801
01:00:19,600 --> 01:00:24,560
I also learned a lot about fraud, and how 
to do it both on purpose and by accident.

802
01:00:24,560 --> 01:00:29,600
The term “rug pull” with its derivations “rug” and 
“rugged”, all to describe projects that made big  

803
01:00:29,600 --> 01:00:34,880
promises but then took the money and ran, embedded 
themselves in my vocabulary extremely quickly.

804
01:00:34,880 --> 01:00:38,320
The market is just absolutely 
lousy with fraud and deception.

805
01:00:38,320 --> 01:00:42,080
Wash trading, where you sell something 
to your own sockpuppets in order to lure  

806
01:00:42,080 --> 01:00:45,440
in a real buyer who thinks they’re 
getting a good deal, is rampant.

807
01:00:45,440 --> 01:00:49,440
Market manipulation is so common and 
accepted that it’s actually considered bad  

808
01:00:49,440 --> 01:00:54,560
form if project leaders don’t actively engage 
in it, like it’s considered disrespectful  

809
01:00:54,560 --> 01:01:00,080
to the buyers if the project leaders 
don’t help inflate the resale price.

810
01:01:00,080 --> 01:01:04,000
Also, and I really should not leave 
this merely implied, the art is bad,  

811
01:01:04,000 --> 01:01:06,240
but not in any sort of interesting way.

812
01:01:06,240 --> 01:01:08,640
It’s bad in a smoothed over copycat way,  

813
01:01:08,640 --> 01:01:14,080
a low effort garbage dump from artists who have 
largely given up on having ideas or opinions.

814
01:01:14,080 --> 01:01:16,640
Derivative, lazy, ugly, hollow, and boring.

815
01:01:16,640 --> 01:01:20,320
The capacity for original thought long having 
been drained out of the illustrators kept in  

816
01:01:20,320 --> 01:01:24,080
the employ and proximity of people who 
refuse to shut up about cryptocurrency,  

817
01:01:24,080 --> 01:01:29,120
there is an overwhelming tendency to fall 
back on stale memes and self-flattery.

818
01:01:29,120 --> 01:01:34,480
A massive volume of cryptocurrency art ends 
up being art about cryptocurrency, transparent  

819
01:01:34,480 --> 01:01:39,760
pandering to an audience that is either deeply 
stupid or easily pleased and quite possibly both.

820
01:01:39,760 --> 01:01:43,200
Absent any artistic insight, the vacuum 
is instead filled to overflowing with  

821
01:01:43,200 --> 01:01:46,960
references to doge memes, Bitcoin, 
ethereum, stonks, to the moon,  

822
01:01:46,960 --> 01:01:51,760
buy the dip, good morning, and desperate 
pleas for sempai Elon Musk to notice them,  

823
01:01:51,760 --> 01:01:55,680
all presented with the earnestness and 
authenticity of a Pickle Rick bong.

824
01:01:55,680 --> 01:01:58,960
It's tempting to say that my 
approach, accepting every spam invite,  

825
01:01:58,960 --> 01:02:03,840
was a really flawed way to delve deeper, 
that "obviously" accepting invites from  

826
01:02:03,840 --> 01:02:09,280
spam bots would mainly lead me into less 
stable projects, but surprisingly no.

827
01:02:09,280 --> 01:02:13,440
I got just as much spam for successful 
projects like Humanoids and NFT Worlds  

828
01:02:13,440 --> 01:02:16,640
as I did for rug-pulls like 
Crypto Astronuts and Hood Punks.

829
01:02:16,640 --> 01:02:20,080
On the whole, if you just look at the 
pitch package and the sample product,  

830
01:02:20,080 --> 01:02:24,560
there's very little material difference between 
a project that's gonna sell out 10,000 tokens  

831
01:02:24,560 --> 01:02:28,800
in six hours and one that's going to become a 
trash fire as the project leader has a nervous  

832
01:02:28,800 --> 01:02:33,200
breakdown and burns the mint three days 
post-launch after only selling 800 tokens.

833
01:02:33,200 --> 01:02:37,120
Party Ape Billionaire Club sold 
out, bringing in about $3.2 million,  

834
01:02:37,120 --> 01:02:40,400
and are now flexing their wealth by 
partnering with other crypto projects  

835
01:02:40,400 --> 01:02:46,080
like the 2chains-produced NFT cartoon 
show The Red Ape Family, which just  

836
01:02:46,080 --> 01:02:50,720
really, truly shows off the community’s 
deep pockets and commitment to quality.

837
01:02:50,720 --> 01:02:52,960
[humming noise]

838
01:02:52,960 --> 01:02:57,600
Deep in their roadmap is the promise that 
they will start production on an MMORPG,  

839
01:02:57,600 --> 01:03:00,480
a claim that buyers are entirely faithful in.

840
01:03:00,480 --> 01:03:09,840
Crypto Astronuts sold 1262 of their 9485 tokens, 
bringing in an impressive $375,000. But as nice as  

841
01:03:09,840 --> 01:03:14,018
that number is, it’s not remotely enough to even 
start proceeding with their plan to build a full  

842
01:03:14,018 --> 01:03:19,440
scale PvP-based MMO. Following the failed mint 
in October the devs slowly went quiet and then,  

843
01:03:19,440 --> 01:03:25,200
bit by bit, websites, social media accounts, and 
eventually the Discord itself all disappeared.

844
01:03:25,200 --> 01:03:30,960
Based off the ostensible product, why should 
one of these succeed and the other fail?

845
01:03:30,960 --> 01:03:35,600
The key distinction, ultimately, between a Party 
Ape Billionaire Club and a Crypto Astronuts  

846
01:03:35,600 --> 01:03:40,400
is that PABC was already flush with cash and 
able to manufacture hype with high-priced  

847
01:03:40,400 --> 01:03:44,560
giveaways and expensive advertising. 
Buying advertising space in Times Square,  

848
01:03:44,560 --> 01:03:46,880
in particular, is a specific fixation.

849
01:03:46,880 --> 01:03:49,600
But running a 10 second ad 
every eight minutes on one  

850
01:03:49,600 --> 01:03:53,760
out of the way billboard in Times Square 
isn’t effective advertising, not externally.

851
01:03:53,760 --> 01:03:56,400
All it’s really good for is internal propaganda,  

852
01:03:56,400 --> 01:04:01,040
making insiders feel like the money that 
they’ve spent is buying credibility.

853
01:04:01,040 --> 01:04:04,720
And if you’re in a speculative bubble, 
betting that someone down the line will  

854
01:04:04,720 --> 01:04:09,680
buy you out for more than you bought in, 
credibility is worth everything in the world.

855
01:04:15,840 --> 01:04:17,040
This is pervasive.

856
01:04:17,040 --> 01:04:21,840
Even in the most established projects, ones that 
have been going for years, there's not really an  

857
01:04:21,840 --> 01:04:27,520
underlying thing, these aren't fandoms in the 
way you would experience them around a game  

858
01:04:27,520 --> 01:04:33,840
or a TV show or a book, the product is pretty 
insubstantial if not functionally non-existent.

859
01:04:33,840 --> 01:04:36,160
This is where these projects diverge significantly  

860
01:04:36,160 --> 01:04:39,360
from the artworks that drove the 
speculative mania in the spring.

861
01:04:39,360 --> 01:04:43,280
They’re not positioning themselves as 
art that is worth possessing for the art,  

862
01:04:43,280 --> 01:04:49,600
as flimsy and illusory as that claim was, 
but as ongoing projects that you buy into.

863
01:04:49,600 --> 01:04:54,560
The purchase of a token is an abstracted 
version of buying early stock in a company,  

864
01:04:54,560 --> 01:05:00,480
a venture-capital style investment in 
promises, which is a very significant mutation.

865
01:05:00,480 --> 01:05:04,240
Okay, so what do these phantom 
companies claim to exist to do?

866
01:05:04,800 --> 01:05:09,120
Pretty much all of them promise direct 
financial returns in some way shape or form.

867
01:05:09,120 --> 01:05:12,560
Sometimes this is just a nebulous 
sense that the whole thing will go  

868
01:05:12,560 --> 01:05:16,960
“to the moon”, meaning the value of the tokens 
will take off and thus early buyers will be able  

869
01:05:16,960 --> 01:05:22,000
to resell for huge profits, or more direct as 
the project leaders promise the formation of,  

870
01:05:22,000 --> 01:05:27,520
effectively, an unofficial hedge fund investing 
a communal pool into other crypto products.

871
01:05:27,520 --> 01:05:31,280
Probably the funniest of all of these was 
Betting Kongs, which wanted to create an  

872
01:05:31,280 --> 01:05:34,720
unregulated real money casino 
in which token holders would be,  

873
01:05:34,720 --> 01:05:40,560
explicitly, part owners, and also permitted 
to gamble in the casino that they owned.

874
01:05:40,560 --> 01:05:46,480
“Betting Kongs is not your ordinary NFT 
project, we aim to create passive income  

875
01:05:46,480 --> 01:05:51,520
for our NFT owners by co-owning 
a casino with a profit split.”

876
01:05:51,520 --> 01:05:55,440
“Welcome to the whitepaper fellow gamblers!”

877
01:05:55,440 --> 01:06:00,720
“Why are we doing this? To put it short, 
we love gambling and noticed how a lot  

878
01:06:00,720 --> 01:06:06,080
of the operators out there are owned by large 
corporations who have no care for the community  

879
01:06:06,080 --> 01:06:11,520
of the service they provide… We want to 
provide a project where everyone playing  

880
01:06:11,520 --> 01:06:15,920
can be a co-owner of the place they’re 
playing at and make money from it all.”

881
01:06:16,560 --> 01:06:21,680
Failure was probably the best outcome for 
everyone, here, if we’re being honest.

882
01:06:21,680 --> 01:06:25,440
Some promise this in the form of 
a more conventional media project,  

883
01:06:25,440 --> 01:06:29,680
like a comic book or a cartoon 
or a movie, or all of the above.

884
01:06:30,320 --> 01:06:37,120
“We have planned the creation of a series 
of comics dedicated to the pixel girl”

885
01:06:37,120 --> 01:06:43,840
“The key image is static, or at least we think so 
now. But the squeaky girl is still a seductress so  

886
01:06:43,840 --> 01:06:50,720
the image of breasts will be presented in various 
variations that our community will approve.”

887
01:06:51,280 --> 01:06:58,880
“Let’s imagine, there are 5,000 NFTITs holders. 
There is a 30 million market of comics lovers in  

888
01:06:58,880 --> 01:07:06,720
the US… On average every comics lover spends 
around 20 USD per comic per week. It means  

889
01:07:06,720 --> 01:07:15,120
80$ per month and 960$ per year. The total 
addressable market is worth 28,800,000,000  

890
01:07:18,880 --> 01:07:28,400
USD. Let’s imagine that we take 1% 
of this market. It’s 288,000,000 USD  

891
01:07:28,960 --> 01:07:37,840
per year on the base of monthly subscriptions 
raised in crypto. This is a cash flow.”

892
01:07:38,400 --> 01:07:42,320
“Nice to see some active communication, 
and appreciate the effort (as announced  

893
01:07:42,320 --> 01:07:46,320
this afternoon) trying to resurrect 
this project into something successful…  

894
01:07:46,320 --> 01:07:46,880
The proposed path forward announced this afternoon 
is intriguing and am prepared to support. The only  

895
01:07:46,880 --> 01:07:50,960
thing I would also like to see, assuming the 
project can be successfully turned around  

896
01:07:50,960 --> 01:07:55,440
is to perhaps, in addition to some revenue 
sharing, have some revenue donated to Breast  

897
01:07:55,440 --> 01:08:00,240
Cancer Research. To truly enjoy them, 
we should keep them happy and healthy!”

898
01:08:00,240 --> 01:08:06,080
As already implied, many of them promise video 
games, often an MMO, but just as often, like,  

899
01:08:07,040 --> 01:08:10,320
just the concept of a video game?

900
01:08:10,880 --> 01:08:13,280
Okay, wait, let me word that another way.

901
01:08:13,280 --> 01:08:15,680
They will promise “a video game”.

902
01:08:15,680 --> 01:08:21,200
Like, that’s the promise, in its entirety. 
No clues for genre, style, scope, engine,  

903
01:08:21,200 --> 01:08:26,240
or platform or how any of the tokens would 
interact with it. Just “a video game.” If  

904
01:08:26,240 --> 01:08:33,920
we sell 10,000 tokens for $300 each we will start 
brainstorming development ideas for a video game.

905
01:08:33,920 --> 01:08:37,840
Now, all of these tend to be in collections 
of ten thousand, and there’s actually an  

906
01:08:37,840 --> 01:08:40,000
interesting sort of quirk inside that.

907
01:08:40,000 --> 01:08:41,840
The initial format was to mint an  

908
01:08:41,840 --> 01:08:45,120
entire collection and just 
shove them out onto the market.

909
01:08:45,120 --> 01:08:48,800
The cap comes into play purely 
because you have to tell the program  

910
01:08:48,800 --> 01:08:51,439
generating the garbage when to stop.

911
01:08:51,439 --> 01:08:55,279
However as the scheme started to 
take off and competition rose,  

912
01:08:55,279 --> 01:08:59,679
it became obvious that this was a sucker’s 
way of doing it because that meant paying gas  

913
01:08:59,680 --> 01:09:02,000
fees on everything up front, plus 
the gas fees on the actual sale.

914
01:09:02,000 --> 01:09:06,000
So someone came up with a system for 
minting a random output on demand which  

915
01:09:06,000 --> 01:09:08,960
shuffles the mint cost off onto the buyer.

916
01:09:08,960 --> 01:09:11,600
From there it all took off like wildfire.

917
01:09:11,600 --> 01:09:16,080
Very low up-front cost, extremely low 
risk, plus it turns the entire system  

918
01:09:16,080 --> 01:09:19,680
into a gacha game with different 
rarity curves for attributes.

919
01:09:19,680 --> 01:09:24,800
At best these are all obfuscated 
gambling schemes, at worst active scams.

920
01:09:24,800 --> 01:09:31,520
And the payoff of failure makes it extremely 
difficult to parse one from the other.

921
01:09:31,520 --> 01:09:37,360
World of Wojak only sold 20 tokens to 
11 people and still pocketed over $5000.

922
01:09:38,479 --> 01:09:44,319
Pro Camel Riders sold 114 tokens 
to 71 buyers and took home $25,000.

923
01:09:45,279 --> 01:09:53,919
METAMONZ sold 722 of their 9999 tokens to 
343 buyers and walked off with $211,000.

924
01:09:55,040 --> 01:10:03,120
Since the average buy-in is over $350, the payday 
for failure makes it irrational to succeed.

925
01:10:03,120 --> 01:10:06,960
The interesting aspect of it all, 
though, is the emergent fiction of it.

926
01:10:06,960 --> 01:10:11,120
These smoke vendors don’t have an actual 
product more complex than the output of  

927
01:10:11,120 --> 01:10:16,640
a vending machine in the front of a grocery 
store, so they need a story to sell instead,  

928
01:10:16,640 --> 01:10:21,440
and so we get this wave of poorly defined 
projects pitching a token with an attached  

929
01:10:21,440 --> 01:10:25,680
jpg that represents the concept of a 
thing that could become a future business.

930
01:10:25,680 --> 01:10:30,080
What that business does is unimportant, 
and indeed many of these projects,  

931
01:10:30,080 --> 01:10:35,120
successful and otherwise, trade in a 
flattering myth of decentralization  

932
01:10:35,120 --> 01:10:39,040
where the direction of the business, 
down to its fundamental product,  

933
01:10:39,040 --> 01:10:44,880
is shunted into the indeterminate future to 
be decided later by collective consensus.

934
01:10:44,880 --> 01:10:50,960
Are we a comic book, a movie, a hedge fund, a 
casino, or a bimonthly curated box of snacks?  

935
01:10:50,960 --> 01:10:53,840
Well that’s for the token holders to decide.

936
01:10:53,840 --> 01:10:58,080
All that matters is that whatever 
it is, it will definitely  

937
01:10:58,080 --> 01:11:02,800
make the value of your tokens go up, 
so you should definitely buy two.

938
01:11:04,240 --> 01:11:08,720
“One thing I learned about NFTs, if you think 
something’s going to be a blue chip, you should  

939
01:11:08,720 --> 01:11:12,640
definitely buy at least two, because you’re going 
to get one, emotionally attached to one of them  

940
01:11:13,520 --> 01:11:17,360
and you’re not going to want to sell it, because 
NFTs are going to explode all over the world.

941
01:11:17,360 --> 01:11:22,880
And if you’ve got a blue chip today it’s going 
to be incredibly more valuable in five years  

942
01:11:22,880 --> 01:11:26,640
from now, or even three years from now, or 
even two years from now, than it is today.”

943
01:11:26,640 --> 01:11:30,640
On the front of otherwise respectable, or 
at least established, brands and people  

944
01:11:30,640 --> 01:11:35,200
getting into NFTs the results tend to 
be extremely tepid and insubstantial,  

945
01:11:35,200 --> 01:11:41,520
even by the standards of NFTs; very low-risk, 
low-quality, low-engagement tokens shoveled out  

946
01:11:41,520 --> 01:11:45,920
the door to capitalize on a hot buzzword, 
chasing the cash that’s sloshing around.

947
01:11:50,440 --> 01:11:51,440
[Drumming]

948
01:11:51,440 --> 01:11:54,720
Tied up in all this, there's an 
extremely pervasive resistance to  

949
01:11:54,720 --> 01:11:59,520
any form of skepticism that ultimately 
manifests as a sort of toxic positivity.

950
01:11:59,520 --> 01:12:02,400
This is all part of a complex feedback loop.

951
01:12:02,400 --> 01:12:06,960
The projects, broadly speaking, lack any 
kind of substantial product, existing almost  

952
01:12:06,960 --> 01:12:12,640
entirely as promises backed by nothing more than 
a screenshot of a roadmap and some sample PFPs.

953
01:12:12,640 --> 01:12:14,800
And, again, I think it's really important to keep  

954
01:12:14,800 --> 01:12:18,640
in mind that that goes for successful 
projects just as much as for rug-pulls.

955
01:12:18,640 --> 01:12:21,680
There really isn't any meaningful 
difference between a Party Ape  

956
01:12:21,680 --> 01:12:23,600
Billionaire Club and a Betting Kongs.

957
01:12:23,600 --> 01:12:28,480
Betting Kongs were never going to make a casino, 
even if they hadn't tanked, and despite the fact  

958
01:12:28,480 --> 01:12:34,000
that they were running billboards in Time 
Square PABC is never making an MMORPG.

959
01:12:34,000 --> 01:12:38,880
Both claims are equally ridiculous, but 
one of the two made a huge pile of money.

960
01:12:38,880 --> 01:12:43,680
The primary product is ultimately hype, 
which is both insubstantial and fickle.

961
01:12:43,680 --> 01:12:48,400
Negativity, both internal and external, can 
have a meaningful impact on the willingness  

962
01:12:48,400 --> 01:12:53,600
of people to buy into a project, and if buyers 
are tepid then you won't get a runaway sale,  

963
01:12:53,600 --> 01:12:58,000
and if you don't get a runaway sale then 
that's going to turn off buyers even more,  

964
01:12:58,000 --> 01:13:02,240
which means the secondary market for 
tokens will likely fail to materialize.

965
01:13:02,800 --> 01:13:05,760
This is what makes enthusiasts 
so deeply unreliable.

966
01:13:05,760 --> 01:13:09,280
They have meaningful financial 
stake in an intangible, volatile  

967
01:13:09,280 --> 01:13:12,160
thing that exists entirely 
as a collective ideoform,  

968
01:13:12,160 --> 01:13:17,600
a story about a potential future outcome, whose 
value is based entirely on public perception.

969
01:13:17,600 --> 01:13:21,840
You can’t trust what they have to say because 
they’re currently holding a hot potato,  

970
01:13:21,840 --> 01:13:24,800
and as much as they insist that they just really,  

971
01:13:24,800 --> 01:13:28,080
really enjoy the feeling of a 
burning hot potato in their hands,

972
01:13:28,800 --> 01:13:29,680
do they?

973
01:13:29,680 --> 01:13:31,760
Or are they just hoping that you’ll catch it?

974
01:13:31,760 --> 01:13:34,640
This creates an environment of 
toxic positivity where doubt  

975
01:13:34,640 --> 01:13:36,960
is aggressively policed by both project leaders,

976
01:13:36,960 --> 01:13:41,440
who have an obvious financial interest in hype 
since their big payday is the minting rush,

977
01:13:41,440 --> 01:13:46,240
and community members themselves, who have 
a speculative financial interest in hype.

978
01:13:46,240 --> 01:13:50,880
While all of that is logical in the pure sense 
that there's an effect that can be explained by  

979
01:13:50,880 --> 01:13:55,520
an incentive, the output is effectively 
a self-organizing high-control group.

980
01:13:55,520 --> 01:13:58,240
Doubters are ostracized so aggressively  

981
01:13:58,240 --> 01:14:02,400
that it chills all conversation 
about a project's actual viability.

982
01:14:02,400 --> 01:14:06,880
All concerns are just FUD: 
fear, uncertainty, and doubt.

983
01:14:06,880 --> 01:14:10,560
Questions that would be utterly 
banal in any other investment forum,  

984
01:14:10,560 --> 01:14:13,200
what has the team done, what assets do they have,  

985
01:14:13,200 --> 01:14:18,320
why should anyone believe they can deliver 
on their promises, are treated as hostile.

986
01:14:18,320 --> 01:14:21,680
And the frank reality is 
because there aren't answers.

987
01:14:21,680 --> 01:14:25,280
Party Ape Billionaire Club is 
just as vaporous, and yet they  

988
01:14:25,280 --> 01:14:31,440
superficially succeeded, so there's 
incentive to enforce the collective illusion.

989
01:14:31,440 --> 01:14:35,280
This is multiplied by an internal 
form of performative etiquette.

990
01:14:35,280 --> 01:14:38,720
Participants ritualistically wish each 
other good morning and good night,  

991
01:14:38,720 --> 01:14:41,200
boiled down to the shorthand GM and GN.

992
01:14:41,200 --> 01:14:46,240
That seems like a small thing, there’s nothing 
inherently suspicious about good morning or  

993
01:14:46,240 --> 01:14:52,480
good night, but in observed practice it’s a very 
distinct ritual, not merely a shibboleth, but a  

994
01:14:52,480 --> 01:14:58,800
repetitive action that signals in-group membership 
and affirms loyalty on an ongoing basis.

995
