1027
01:17:18,960 --> 01:17:23,600
So the question, then, is what 
do the tokens actually do?

1028
01:17:24,240 --> 01:17:29,040
As mentioned before the token itself is just 
a box that a bit of data can be put into.

1029
01:17:29,040 --> 01:17:31,040
Now, this box is extremely small,  

1030
01:17:31,040 --> 01:17:35,600
to the point that even an average cell phone 
photograph is several times too large to fit.

1031
01:17:35,600 --> 01:17:37,280
Due to the nature of the chain,  

1032
01:17:37,280 --> 01:17:41,920
updating software that’s put onto the 
chain is both difficult and expensive.

1033
01:17:41,920 --> 01:17:45,520
Complicated programs need to be 
broken up into multiple tokens each  

1034
01:17:45,520 --> 01:17:48,800
containing a smart contract that 
defines a portion of the whole,  

1035
01:17:48,800 --> 01:17:52,320
and all of these contracts need to 
interlink and reference each other,

1036
01:17:52,320 --> 01:17:58,560
but with an eye towards the fact that 
each transaction that either computes or  

1037
01:17:58,560 --> 01:18:05,280
alters information requires paying processing 
fees, only reading information is free.

1038
01:18:05,280 --> 01:18:10,080
The process of fixing a bug in a smart contract 
basically amounts to minting a new copy of the  

1039
01:18:10,080 --> 01:18:15,120
contract and then jumping through some hoops 
to re-name the old and new contract so that  

1040
01:18:15,120 --> 01:18:19,520
the new copy has the name that any other 
interacting contracts are looking for,  

1041
01:18:19,520 --> 01:18:23,280
paying fees for just about 
every step of that process.

1042
01:18:23,280 --> 01:18:27,680
This creates a very funny Catch 22 where 
on one hand is the insistence that the  

1043
01:18:27,680 --> 01:18:32,880
NFTs that end users buy are potentially 
extremely powerful, able to be miniature  

1044
01:18:32,880 --> 01:18:38,480
self-governing applets that exist in a 
web of like applets, and on the other hand  

1045
01:18:38,480 --> 01:18:43,120
is a large stack of incentives to 
put as little into them as possible.

1046
01:18:43,120 --> 01:18:47,840
For an example of the pitfalls, Wolf Game 
was a somewhat popular NFT based gambling  

1047
01:18:47,840 --> 01:18:52,640
game that bragged about being hosted 
entirely on-chain, at great expense.  

1048
01:18:52,640 --> 01:18:57,600
Everything from the pixel art wolves and sheep 
to the game’s code was stored on Ethereum.

1049
01:18:57,600 --> 01:19:03,200
The idea behind the game is that users would mint 
a character token, which had a 90% chance of being  

1050
01:19:03,200 --> 01:19:08,800
a sheep, and a 10% chance of being a wolf, with 
a finite supply of wolves and sheep available.

1051
01:19:08,800 --> 01:19:14,320
The important thing here is that the character 
tokens weren’t just a bit of art and a serial  

1052
01:19:14,320 --> 01:19:19,680
number, but tiny programs that allowed 
users to perform interactions like staking.

1053
01:19:19,680 --> 01:19:24,400
The problem is that their code was full of 
multiple bugs, and since some of those bugs  

1054
01:19:24,400 --> 01:19:32,480
were contained in the character tokens, they 
were replicated across all 13,809 minted tokens.

1055
01:19:33,120 --> 01:19:38,560
A glitchy token can’t be 
patched, it must be replaced.

1056
01:19:38,560 --> 01:19:43,280
So the Wolf Game devs were forced to 
not only re-deploy all their contracts,  

1057
01:19:43,280 --> 01:19:50,000
but attempt to re-mint and distribute 
identical copies of every token generated.

1058
01:19:50,000 --> 01:19:51,200
It didn’t go well.

1059
01:19:51,760 --> 01:19:55,840
Given the risks inherent in putting 
functionality inside the token itself,  

1060
01:19:55,840 --> 01:19:59,280
and the high cost of interaction, 
the most common application  

1061
01:19:59,280 --> 01:20:04,320
is to use external systems to simply 
check for possession of a token.

1062
01:20:04,320 --> 01:20:09,840
This is where we introduce another player into 
the ecosystem: wallet managers like MetaMask.

1063
01:20:09,840 --> 01:20:14,640
In a few short years the system has already 
grown so bloated and difficult to interact with  

1064
01:20:14,640 --> 01:20:17,200
that it’s become necessary to develop middleware  

1065
01:20:17,200 --> 01:20:20,560
applications that simplify the 
process of generating wallets,  

1066
01:20:20,560 --> 01:20:25,440
switching wallets, and mediating handshakes 
between the wallet and external systems.

1067
01:20:25,440 --> 01:20:29,760
From one point of view these wallet managers 
are the golden key that makes it all work.

1068
01:20:29,760 --> 01:20:35,120
They solve the single-sign on problem allowing 
your web browser to simply know that it’s  

1069
01:20:35,120 --> 01:20:39,920
you who is using it, automatically negotiating 
permissions based on relevant tokens.

1070
01:20:39,920 --> 01:20:44,720
It’s your log in, your credit card, your Steam 
profile, and your bank account all rolled into  

1071
01:20:44,720 --> 01:20:51,520
a single point of contact making interaction with 
Web3, the internet of the future, frictionless.

1072
01:20:51,520 --> 01:20:56,240
From another point of view it’s a massive point 
of failure that contains so much information,  

1073
01:20:56,240 --> 01:21:00,800
so many permissions, so much of worth, that it 
becomes an extremely obvious point of attack,  

1074
01:21:00,800 --> 01:21:04,800
manufactured by idiots who claim to 
be building a security product in 2021  

1075
01:21:04,800 --> 01:21:09,840
that doesn’t obfuscate key phrases within 
the UI or use two factor authentication.

1076
01:21:09,840 --> 01:21:13,440
Remember, again, that these people want 
to put medical records, drivers licenses,  

1077
01:21:13,440 --> 01:21:16,480
professional accreditations, and 
real estate deeds into their system.

1078
01:21:16,480 --> 01:21:17,840
They should not be trusted.

1079
01:21:17,840 --> 01:21:20,400
The entire market is absolutely lousy with scams,  

1080
01:21:20,400 --> 01:21:23,120
and has been since Bitcoin 
first gained any traction.

1081
01:21:23,120 --> 01:21:28,000
Every single scam structure imaginable has been 
dusted off and redeployed into this explicitly  

1082
01:21:28,000 --> 01:21:31,520
unregulated market where victims 
are largely without recourse.

1083
01:21:31,520 --> 01:21:35,360
These range from institutional scams, 
like Ponzi schemes, pump and dumps,  

1084
01:21:35,360 --> 01:21:39,680
and insider trading, to middle-weight 
scams like gold brick and wash trading,  

1085
01:21:39,680 --> 01:21:43,520
to grittier scams like phishing 
and sending fake links.

1086
01:21:43,520 --> 01:21:47,520
Pump and dumps, in particular, are conducted 
in broad daylight, since it’s not illegal,  

1087
01:21:47,520 --> 01:21:51,120
it’s just against the terms of service 
of the exchanges that you use to do it,  

1088
01:21:51,120 --> 01:21:53,920
so the worst case scenario 
is you burn your account.

1089
01:21:53,920 --> 01:21:57,120
They’ll straight up walk you through 
the process of doing a pump and dump,  

1090
01:21:57,120 --> 01:21:59,440
no codewords, diagrams and everything.

1091
01:21:59,440 --> 01:22:03,120
They’re notable as they’re actually 
a two-headed scam because, you see,  

1092
01:22:03,120 --> 01:22:07,040
you might get recruited onto 
the pump half of the scheme,  

1093
01:22:07,040 --> 01:22:12,080
or you might think you’re being recruited 
to pump, but you’re actually the dump.

1094
01:22:12,080 --> 01:22:16,720
As already mentioned, blockchain is resilient to 
direct man-in-the-middle attacks, where someone  

1095
01:22:16,720 --> 01:22:21,920
tries to inject bad data straight into the 
chain, but man in the middle attacks are rare.

1096
01:22:21,920 --> 01:22:26,240
In an environment like cryptocurrency, 
with few, if any, repercussions for  

1097
01:22:26,240 --> 01:22:32,080
misbehaviour that stays within the cryptosphere, 
man-in-the-middle attacks are wholly unnecessary.

1098
01:22:32,080 --> 01:22:36,960
Why try to brute force your bad data onto 
the chain when you can trick someone into  

1099
01:22:36,960 --> 01:22:40,640
giving you access to their wallet, 
then transfer all their stuff out?

1100
01:22:40,640 --> 01:22:44,000
Every smart contract becomes a 
self-rewarding bug bounty where  

1101
01:22:44,000 --> 01:22:48,480
the payout is whatever apes and coins 
you can grab before anyone notices.

1102
01:22:48,480 --> 01:22:50,880
And that’s not even touching 
on the subject of malware!

1103
01:22:50,880 --> 01:22:53,280
Smart contracts are just code, they’re software,  

1104
01:22:53,280 --> 01:22:58,880
there’s no reason they can’t be viruses or worms, 
the primary limitation is processing power.

1105
01:22:58,880 --> 01:23:02,560
But, also, it’s a virus that someone can drop  

1106
01:23:02,560 --> 01:23:07,440
directly into your bankless bank account 
and just wait for you to activate it.

1107
01:23:07,440 --> 01:23:12,000
And, yeah, that’s right, there’s no 
offer/confirmation step in sending  

1108
01:23:12,000 --> 01:23:16,720
tokens back and forth, someone who knows your 
wallet can just drop stuff right into it,

1109
01:23:16,720 --> 01:23:20,000
so, like, pin that somewhere in your brain.

1110
01:23:20,000 --> 01:23:24,480
The best part about this is that the whole 
ecosystem operates on a strict assumption that  

1111
01:23:24,480 --> 01:23:28,480
possession is ownership and access is permission,

1112
01:23:28,480 --> 01:23:30,960
which is absolutely buckwild coming from software  

1113
01:23:30,960 --> 01:23:34,000
developers who claim to be very 
concerned with systems security.

1114
01:23:34,000 --> 01:23:38,240
If someone tricks you into sending 
them your Bored Ape it’s now theirs.

1115
01:23:38,240 --> 01:23:41,680
The only mechanism in the machine 
for parsing legitimate transactions  

1116
01:23:41,680 --> 01:23:44,800
from illegitimate transactions 
is the consensus mechanism,

1117
01:23:44,800 --> 01:23:50,080
which is only concerned with whether or not the 
transactions followed the rules of the software.

1118
01:23:50,080 --> 01:23:55,280
The only illegitimacy it recognizes 
are people trying to insert fake data.

1119
01:23:55,280 --> 01:23:57,840
When you are tricked into doing something  

1120
01:23:57,840 --> 01:24:03,360
all of the mechanics of what follows are, 
by the rules of the system, legitimate.

1121
01:24:03,360 --> 01:24:04,800
It’s a legal transfer.

1122
01:24:04,800 --> 01:24:08,320
More relevant, however, is the 
sheer density of these scams.

1123
01:24:08,320 --> 01:24:13,040
The one market that cryptocurrency has 
successfully disrupted is the market of fraud.

1124
01:24:13,040 --> 01:24:17,200
Think of this this way: a big population of 
people have willingly self-identified that  

1125
01:24:17,200 --> 01:24:22,000
they have substantial disposable income, 
poor judgment, low social literacy,  

1126
01:24:22,000 --> 01:24:26,240
a high tolerance for nonsensical 
risk, and are highly persuadable.

1127
01:24:26,240 --> 01:24:30,160
People who fall victim to these scams 
have basically no options other than  

1128
01:24:30,160 --> 01:24:34,320
taking to social media and attempting to 
whip up enough of a frenzy that they can  

1129
