1142
01:25:41,120 --> 01:25:44,480
A low trust environment is 
also a low privacy environment.

1143
01:25:44,480 --> 01:25:47,520
Anything you do on a blockchain is, by design,  

1144
01:25:47,520 --> 01:25:50,800
accessible to everyone who 
knows how to navigate the data.

1145
01:25:50,800 --> 01:25:55,280
Now, you might be thinking, isn’t that 
the opposite of how it’s supposed to work?

1146
01:25:55,840 --> 01:25:57,680
I thought crypto was all anonymous?

1147
01:25:58,880 --> 01:26:06,320
So, yes, crypto is anonymous by default, there’s 
no inherent requirement for proof of identity,  

1148
01:26:06,320 --> 01:26:10,480
and in fact numerous applications 
that would benefit from a stricter  

1149
01:26:10,480 --> 01:26:14,960
1-to-1 correlation between accounts 
and people struggle with this.

1150
01:26:14,960 --> 01:26:17,920
On forums and social media 
it’s called sockpuppeting,  

1151
01:26:17,920 --> 01:26:21,760
in crypto it’s called a Sibyl attack, 
where users are able to generate  

1152
01:26:21,760 --> 01:26:25,600
numerous alternate identities by 
creating additional accounts or wallets.

1153
01:26:25,600 --> 01:26:30,560
The epidemic of wash trading on OpenSea 
relies on the ability to pretend you’re  

1154
01:26:30,560 --> 01:26:36,160
several different people as you buy apes from 
yourself for hundreds of thousands of dollars.

1155
01:26:36,160 --> 01:26:38,960
