01:57:50,160 --> 01:57:53,360
themselves as a DAO have no 
machine functionality at all.

1593
01:57:53,360 --> 01:57:56,720
It’s pretty standard to find a DAO 
that has issued a governance token,  

1594
01:57:56,720 --> 01:58:02,080
the scrip that’s used for voting, with the 
systems to actually use that token being placed  

1595
01:58:02,080 --> 01:58:04,960
somewhere in the nebulous future of the roadmap.

1596
01:58:04,960 --> 01:58:09,360
That open-endedness is actually important because 
while the claim is that these machines will  

1597
01:58:09,360 --> 01:58:14,960
further democratize the internet, the technical 
complexity that they add, the new specialized  

1598
01:58:14,960 --> 01:58:19,200
programming expertise that they require, 
concentrates a lot of power in the hands  

1599
01:58:19,200 --> 01:58:24,400
of the people who can build the templates that in 
turn enable non-programmers to actually use it.

1600
01:58:24,400 --> 01:58:28,400
It’s just laying the seeds for the 
future recreation of the status quo.

1601
01:58:28,400 --> 01:58:33,840
The Facebook/Google/Amazon dominated internet 
arose because the technical cost of building a  

1602
01:58:33,840 --> 01:58:38,320
modern website rose far beyond what the 
vast majority of amateurs could manage,  

1603
01:58:38,320 --> 01:58:42,480
so everyone moved to templates, and then 
to services, and finally to platforms.

1604
01:58:42,480 --> 01:58:45,600
This doesn’t even reset the clock on that,  

1605
01:58:45,600 --> 01:58:50,640
the technical cost of creating a DAO is 
already far beyond any casual amateur,  

1606
01:58:50,640 --> 01:58:55,440
in part because all of this is being built by 
programmers, and in part because of the stakes.

1607
01:58:55,440 --> 01:58:59,680
The only thing this stuff is truly 
good for is managing on-chain assets.

1608
01:58:59,680 --> 01:59:05,120
A DAO program can see the state of the chain and 
interact with it, so the DAO humans can vote on  

1609
01:59:05,120 --> 01:59:10,240
what should happen to those assets and then the 
DAO program can automatically act on the results.

1610
01:59:10,240 --> 01:59:11,840
But that raises the stakes.

1611
01:59:11,840 --> 01:59:17,280
Because a DAO can see and interact directly 
with on-chain assets there’s the risk that via  

1612
01:59:17,280 --> 01:59:23,680
bad programming or unforeseen exploits a malicious 
actor can use a DAO to access all kinds of stuff.

1613
01:59:23,680 --> 01:59:28,240
The risk is directly proportional to 
the value of the assets kept on-chain,  

1614
01:59:28,240 --> 01:59:33,280
and remember, again, that evangelists 
want to put everything on-chain.

1615
01:59:33,280 --> 01:59:37,040
The hilarious thing is that this 
has already played out once before.

1616
01:59:37,040 --> 01:59:41,440
In fact it played out with the first 
DAO ever built, called The DAO.

1617
01:59:42,080 --> 01:59:46,960
This whole story unfolds over the course of 
three months in 2016, from April to June.

1618
01:59:46,960 --> 01:59:52,480
The DAO was an Ethereum-based venture capital fund 
that aimed to use code to create an investment  

1619
01:59:52,480 --> 01:59:57,360
firm without a conventional management structure 
or board of directors, a scheme that’s positioned  

1620
01:59:57,360 --> 02:00:01,600
as “lightweight” and “reducing bureaucratic 
overhead”, but really it just translated  

1621
02:00:01,600 --> 02:00:06,000
to an attempt at minimizing human liability 
for the actions and behaviours of the fund.

1622
02:00:06,000 --> 02:00:09,360
This unparalleled expression of 
greed made the major speculative  

1623
02:00:09,360 --> 02:00:12,000
players in Ethereum so horny that during the April  

1624
02:00:12,000 --> 02:00:18,880
and May presale they funneled 14% of the entire 
volume of ether into The DAO’s central wallet.

1625
02:00:18,880 --> 02:00:23,840
Now, because The DAO’s underlying code was open 
source, experts and malicious actors alike were  

1626
02:00:23,840 --> 02:00:28,560
able to pour over it for vulnerabilities, 
and, indeed, vulnerabilities were found.

1627
02:00:28,560 --> 02:00:32,880
However, because at the end of the day 
fleshy humans are the ones actually pushing  

1628
02:00:32,880 --> 02:00:37,440
buttons and making decisions, the actual 
leadership of the nominally-leaderless DAO,  

1629
02:00:37,440 --> 02:00:41,280
horny for money and prestige, 
decided to launch in late May anyway.

1630
02:00:41,280 --> 02:00:45,950
Three weeks later The DAO’s programming was 
exploited and the attacker was able to transfer  

1631
02:00:45,950 --> 02:00:52,160
1/3rd of The DAO’s funds into a holding wallet, 
about 5% of the entire Ethereum economy,  

1632
02:00:52,160 --> 02:00:55,600
valued at the time around 
16 to 17 million dollars.

1633
02:00:55,600 --> 02:00:59,040
Now, because this threatened the 
bottom line of capital holders,  

1634
02:00:59,040 --> 02:01:03,200
the Ethereum project as a whole, the 
entire thing, was almost immediately  

1635
02:01:03,200 --> 02:01:06,720
forked in order to undo the hack and 
protect the interests of the wealthy.

1636
02:01:06,720 --> 02:01:11,200
Ethereum Classic, the arm of the fork that 
didn’t undo the attack, persists to this day,  

1637
02:01:11,200 --> 02:01:15,120
though it’s notably less popular despite 
being demonstrably more principled.

1638
02:01:15,120 --> 02:01:17,760
Because all the talk about 
“decentralization” is a myth.

1639
02:01:17,760 --> 02:01:18,720
It’s just words.

1640
02:01:18,720 --> 02:01:23,200
At the end of the day the guys in charge, the guys 
who built the system to serve their interests,  

1641
02:01:23,200 --> 02:01:26,000
are still in charge and keep a 
killswitch in their back pocket.

1642
02:01:26,000 --> 02:01:31,920
Crypto is barely a decade old and organizations 
deemed too big to fail already exist.

1643
02:01:31,920 --> 02:01:34,720
The whole fiasco laid out 
the truth from the word go:  

1644
02:01:34,720 --> 02:01:39,840
calling a DAO a revolutionary structure is 
smoke and mirrors, it’s just voting shares.

1645
02:01:39,840 --> 02:01:43,120
You might as well call Apple “a bold 
experiment in democracy” because  

1646
02:01:43,120 --> 02:01:46,720
a baker’s dozen individuals make 
the decisions instead of just one.

1647
02:01:46,720 --> 02:01:50,720
Regardless of the future pitfalls, 
DAOs are also extremely limited.

1648
02:01:50,720 --> 02:01:52,400
They are, again, just code.

1649
02:01:52,400 --> 02:01:55,920
While evangelists promise that they 
can reinvent the social organization,  

1650
02:01:55,920 --> 02:01:59,920
mentally consider all the problems, 
conflicts, and decision making that  

1651
02:01:59,920 --> 02:02:06,480
social organizations deal with and ask how 
many of those even can be solved by code.

1652
02:02:06,480 --> 02:02:09,440
Some of them can easily be 
turned into computer programs.

1653
02:02:09,440 --> 02:02:13,440
Automated bookkeeping, payouts, 
collections, data tracking, sure,  

1654
02:02:13,440 --> 02:02:17,040
that’s all stuff organizations 
conceptually can make use of.

1655
02:02:17,040 --> 02:02:21,840
But how do you code for the fact that Red 
just really doesn’t get along with Blue?

1656
02:02:21,840 --> 02:02:26,000
The pitch promises organizations 
bound by unbreakable rules,  

1657
02:02:26,000 --> 02:02:30,480
but how many organizations actually 
benefit from that level of rigidity?

1658
02:02:30,480 --> 02:02:35,280
In particular what happens when the 
version of the rules enforced by code  

1659
02:02:35,280 --> 02:02:38,880
run up against a complication 
that the coders didn’t consider?

1660
02:02:38,880 --> 02:02:41,360
What happens if someone with 
legitimate stake in the DAO  

1661
02:02:41,360 --> 02:02:44,960
starts spamming the organization’s 
internal systems with bad requests?

1662
02:02:44,960 --> 02:02:47,440
What if not enough people participate in voting?

1663
02:02:47,440 --> 02:02:49,600
What if the system locks itself up?

1664
02:02:49,600 --> 02:02:51,440
What if the rules are rigged?

1665
02:02:51,440 --> 02:02:54,320
What if the system commits a crime?

1666
02:02:54,320 --> 02:02:59,360
If this technology did see mass adoption, a future 
timebomb already exists in the fact that very,  

1667
02:02:59,360 --> 02:03:04,320
very few of these systems have factored mortality 
into the considerations of their structures,  

1668
02:03:04,320 --> 02:03:09,680
because “what if someone with an important token 
dies?” is a really easy thing to overlook when  

1669
02:03:09,680 --> 02:03:14,640
you’re the kind of insulated techbro who reinvents 
vending machines and calls them Bodega Boxes.

1670
02:03:14,640 --> 02:03:19,920
Now, all of these hypotheticals are technically 
addressable, you can build contingency systems  

1671
02:03:19,920 --> 02:03:24,480
that can account for them, but then 
you need to consider contingencies  

1672
02:03:24,480 --> 02:03:28,480
for those contingencies, because what if 
someone uses systems intended for dealing  

1673
02:03:28,480 --> 02:03:32,480
with deceased or absentee members to 
expel people they just don’t like?

1674
02:03:32,480 --> 02:03:35,120
And, again, you can only use code to enforce  

1675
02:03:35,120 --> 02:03:38,480
interactions that the programmers 
make enforceable via the code.

1676
02:03:38,480 --> 02:03:43,680
ConstitutionDAO, a hastily set up scheme to bid on 
one of the few remaining original copies of the US  

1677
02:03:43,680 --> 02:03:48,560
constitution, already ran aground most of these 
problems as the project failed to win the auction  

1678
02:03:48,560 --> 02:03:54,480
and is now trying to issue refunds, a thing that 
the slapdash machine was never intended to do.

1679
02:03:54,480 --> 02:03:58,880
The reality is that most organizations 
with any meaningful social complexity,  

1680
02:03:58,880 --> 02:04:05,360
even tiny organizations like video game guilds, 
are too complex to properly express in code.  

1681
02:04:05,360 --> 02:04:10,320
There’s too many contingencies and contingencies 
for those contingencies and contingencies for  

1682
02:04:10,320 --> 02:04:15,600
those contingencies to account for, so rather 
than trying to turn social interactions into code  

1683
02:04:15,600 --> 02:04:21,360
the DAO is marginalized into only handling 
code-appropriate tasks, like bookkeeping,  

1684
02:04:21,360 --> 02:04:24,960
digital signature verification, 
and on-chain asset management.

1685
02:04:24,960 --> 02:04:30,480
But that’s not a revolutionary new way to 
organize people, that’s just a productivity tool.

1686
02:04:30,480 --> 02:04:34,320
The DAO can have a process for voting on 
actions, but the moment the outcomes of  

1687
02:04:34,320 --> 02:04:40,000
those actions move off-chain, i.e. into the 
real world, the DAO program is powerless.

1688
02:04:40,000 --> 02:04:43,680
The program can’t make humans 
execute the decisions of the group,  

1689
02:04:43,680 --> 02:04:45,920
that’s still an analog problem.

1690
02:04:45,920 --> 02:04:50,160
The whole thing very quickly runs into 
an incentive wall where it’s just faster  

1691
02:04:50,160 --> 02:04:55,840
and easier to solve problems verbally, via 
abstract trust relationships and promises,  

1692
02:04:55,840 --> 02:04:57,920
to the same end results.

1693
02:04:57,920 --> 02:05:02,640
This is why it’s so common for DAOs to not 
actually have any of the inner machine that  

1694
02:05:02,640 --> 02:05:07,120
would actually make them into what they 
claim to be: it’s easier to just not.

1695
02:05:07,120 --> 02:05:10,400
Taken as a whole DAOs aren’t some 
revolutionary new model, they’re a  

1696
02:05:10,400 --> 02:05:15,280
tool built onto the side of cryptocurrency that 
only has meaningful advantages when interacting  

1697
02:05:15,280 --> 02:05:20,240
with cryptocurrency as a tool for speculative 
trading and managing financial instruments.

1698
02:05:20,240 --> 02:05:25,200
The rest is just a gimmick, a slow, 
inflexible tool for executing straw polls.

1699
02:05:25,200 --> 02:05:30,240
Again, a lot of these boil down to a scheme to 
minimize liability on the part of the creators.

